1
00:03:35,709 --> 00:03:36,959
(SOBBING)

2
00:03:42,799 --> 00:03:44,216
SON: Dad.

3
00:04:14,456 --> 00:04:16,081
(WAVES CRASHING)

4
00:04:56,498 --> 00:04:58,082
(MOTOR HUMMING)

5
00:05:23,233 --> 00:05:24,608
(RETCHING)

6
00:05:29,906 --> 00:05:34,159
Clear the ramp! 30 seconds!
God be with you!

7
00:05:34,244 --> 00:05:39,498
Port side stick, starboard side stick,
move fast and clear those murder holes.

8
00:05:39,583 --> 00:05:41,917
I want to see plenty of beach
between men.

9
00:05:42,002 --> 00:05:45,921
Five men is a juicy opportunity.
One man is a waste of ammo.

10
00:05:46,006 --> 00:05:48,090
Keep the sand out of your weapons.

11
00:05:48,216 --> 00:05:52,595
Keep those actions clear.
And I'll see you on the beach.

12
00:05:52,929 --> 00:05:54,388
(EXPLOSIONS)

13
00:06:24,753 --> 00:06:26,962
CAPTAIN: Clear the murder holes!

14
00:06:27,881 --> 00:06:29,715
(BULLETS BUZZING)

15
00:06:43,313 --> 00:06:44,855
Over the side!

16
00:06:51,363 --> 00:06:53,781
CAPTAIN: Port and starboard, over...

17
00:07:30,610 --> 00:07:32,528
(CONTINUOUS EXPLOSIONS)

18
00:07:50,046 --> 00:07:51,714
(FAINT SCREAMING)

19
00:07:58,179 --> 00:07:59,471
(GASPING)

20
00:08:02,976 --> 00:08:04,226
Jesus.

21
00:08:04,686 --> 00:08:06,437
Thank you...

22
00:08:13,403 --> 00:08:15,362
(BULLETS HITTING METAL)

23
00:09:18,176 --> 00:09:19,802
(SOUND DISTORTS)

24
00:09:39,405 --> 00:09:40,823
(EXPLOSION)

25
00:10:20,655 --> 00:10:22,114
(MOUTHING)

26
00:10:25,326 --> 00:10:28,370
I said, what the hell do we do now, sir?

27
00:10:29,831 --> 00:10:33,041
HORVATH: Captain Miller!
Captain Miller!

28
00:10:34,711 --> 00:10:37,880
- Captain Miller!
- Sergeant Horvath!

29
00:10:39,424 --> 00:10:43,093
Move your men off the beach! Go!

30
00:10:43,219 --> 00:10:44,511
Okay, you guys!

31
00:10:44,596 --> 00:10:47,681
- Get on my ass! Follow me!
- Sir!

32
00:10:48,057 --> 00:10:50,058
What's the rallying point?

33
00:10:50,185 --> 00:10:51,977
Anywhere but here!

34
00:10:53,396 --> 00:10:55,355
(CONTINUOUS EXPLOSIONS)

35
00:11:05,074 --> 00:11:07,534
The seawall! Move up to the seawall!

36
00:11:07,619 --> 00:11:09,912
SOLDIER: Sir, I'm staying!

37
00:11:09,996 --> 00:11:12,289
Clear this beach!
Make way for the others!

38
00:11:12,415 --> 00:11:14,958
This is all we got
between us and the Almighty.

39
00:11:15,084 --> 00:11:19,087
Every inch of this beach
has been pre-sighted!

40
00:11:19,964 --> 00:11:23,258
You stay here, you're dead men!

41
00:11:23,509 --> 00:11:25,177
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

42
00:11:36,481 --> 00:11:40,025
Mama! Mama!

43
00:11:41,027 --> 00:11:42,444
(SCREAMING)

44
00:11:44,656 --> 00:11:47,157
Stay down! Stay down!

45
00:11:51,829 --> 00:11:53,163
What are you guys?

46
00:11:53,248 --> 00:11:55,958
104th Medical Battalion, sir!

47
00:11:56,042 --> 00:11:58,710
Here to set up field operations!

48
00:11:58,795 --> 00:12:00,337
Get rid of that crap!

49
00:12:00,421 --> 00:12:03,507
Grab yourselves some weapons.
Follow me.

50
00:12:07,387 --> 00:12:09,137
(SCREAMING IN PAIN)

51
00:12:11,099 --> 00:12:14,017
- BRIGGS: I'm hit! I'm hit!
- Briggs!

52
00:12:18,273 --> 00:12:22,567
Get me out of here. I'm hit low. God!

53
00:12:22,652 --> 00:12:25,737
- Medic!
- Navy Beach Battalion, sir.

54
00:12:25,822 --> 00:12:29,533
I gotta clear these obstacles,
make holes for the tanks.

55
00:12:29,617 --> 00:12:31,952
All the armour is foundering
in the Channel.

56
00:12:32,036 --> 00:12:35,289
Orders, sir. You go somewhere else.
I'm clearing this one!

57
00:12:35,373 --> 00:12:36,873
Come on, Briggs!

58
00:12:36,958 --> 00:12:38,792
(BULLETS BUZZING)

59
00:12:41,754 --> 00:12:43,130
MILLER: Medic!

60
00:12:47,844 --> 00:12:49,469
(SOUND DISTORTS)

61
00:13:20,209 --> 00:13:21,835
MILLER: Move! Move!

62
00:13:29,510 --> 00:13:32,637
Move! Come on! Move!

63
00:13:54,410 --> 00:13:57,746
Shore party.
No armour has made it ashore.

64
00:13:57,830 --> 00:14:02,542
We got no DD tanks on the beach.
Dog One is not open.

65
00:14:03,503 --> 00:14:07,130
- Who's in command here?
- You are, sir!

66
00:14:08,758 --> 00:14:11,218
- Sergeant Horvath!
- Sir!

67
00:14:11,302 --> 00:14:13,345
You recognise where we are?

68
00:14:13,429 --> 00:14:15,847
Right where we're supposed to be,
but no one else is!

69
00:14:15,932 --> 00:14:19,393
Nobody's where they're supposed to be.

70
00:14:19,477 --> 00:14:21,061
Shore party.

71
00:14:21,854 --> 00:14:24,106
First wave, ineffective.

72
00:14:24,190 --> 00:14:28,235
We do not hold the beach.
Say again, we do not hold the beach.

73
00:14:28,611 --> 00:14:29,986
We're all mixed up, sir.

74
00:14:30,071 --> 00:14:31,863
We got the leftovers from Fox Company,

75
00:14:31,948 --> 00:14:33,907
Able Company and George Company!

76
00:14:33,991 --> 00:14:37,619
Plus we got some Navy demo guys
and a beachmaster!

77
00:14:39,163 --> 00:14:42,165
Shore party. Shore party.

78
00:14:48,256 --> 00:14:50,590
CATF, CATF...

79
00:14:54,095 --> 00:14:56,388
- Reiben here, sir!
- Did you see anybody else?

80
00:14:56,472 --> 00:14:59,266
- Jackson, but that's about it.
- Mellish here.

81
00:14:59,350 --> 00:15:02,602
Caparzo! We got DeForest
back there with Wade.

82
00:15:02,687 --> 00:15:06,440
He's hurt so bad he says
he sprung 100 leaks.

83
00:15:06,524 --> 00:15:08,191
Wade says he's all used up.

84
00:15:08,276 --> 00:15:10,527
- Move on to somebody you can help.
- Let's go!

85
00:15:10,611 --> 00:15:13,071
He's battalion surgeon, sir!

86
00:15:17,118 --> 00:15:19,077
- Get his attention.
- Wade!

87
00:15:19,162 --> 00:15:20,662
- Yo, Doc!
- Wade!

88
00:15:20,746 --> 00:15:23,915
- Wade! Wade! Wade!
- Wade!

89
00:15:24,959 --> 00:15:28,253
- Wade! Wade! Wade!
- Too risky, Doc. Too risky.

90
00:15:29,714 --> 00:15:31,798
- Wade!
- All right. Get him off the beach.

91
00:15:31,883 --> 00:15:35,635
I got it! We stopped the bleeding!
We stopped the bleeding!

92
00:15:37,180 --> 00:15:38,805
Fuck!

93
00:15:38,890 --> 00:15:42,184
Just give us a fucking chance,
you son of a bitch!

94
00:15:42,268 --> 00:15:44,686
- Son of a fucking cocksucker!
- MELLISH: Wade! Come on. Come on.

95
00:15:44,770 --> 00:15:47,981
Wade! It's Mellish! Wade!

96
00:15:48,524 --> 00:15:50,192
- Mellish!
- MELLISH: Let's go!

97
00:15:50,276 --> 00:15:51,443
We found Miller!

98
00:15:51,527 --> 00:15:53,737
- Fuck it!
- Let's move! Let's move!

99
00:15:53,821 --> 00:15:55,071
(CRYING)

100
00:16:01,162 --> 00:16:04,289
This is all? This is all that's made it?

101
00:16:04,373 --> 00:16:07,876
We got scattered pretty bad, sir.
There's bound to be more.

102
00:16:08,878 --> 00:16:11,213
- Not enough. It's not enough.
- Dog One exit...

103
00:16:11,297 --> 00:16:12,672
It's gotta be that cut on the right.

104
00:16:12,757 --> 00:16:15,258
- Or is that one on the left? Shit!
- No. No, no, no.

105
00:16:15,343 --> 00:16:18,053
Vierville is to the west of us.
This is Dog One.

106
00:16:18,137 --> 00:16:19,387
They're killing us!

107
00:16:19,472 --> 00:16:23,600
And we don't have a fucking chance,
and that ain't fair!

108
00:16:23,684 --> 00:16:26,061
Gather weapons and ammo!

109
00:16:26,145 --> 00:16:27,979
Gather weapons and ammo!

110
00:16:28,064 --> 00:16:31,149
Come on, let's drag them in
off the sand!

111
00:16:39,242 --> 00:16:43,161
Reiben. Hey, Reiben, Reiben, Reiben,
where's your BAR?

112
00:16:43,913 --> 00:16:46,039
Bottom of the channel, sir.
The bitch tried to drown me.

113
00:16:46,123 --> 00:16:47,999
Find a replacement.

114
00:16:50,044 --> 00:16:53,004
Bangalores! Bring up some bangalores!

115
00:16:54,423 --> 00:16:57,968
Grenades, grenades! Get me
some grenades. Get them over here!

116
00:17:00,638 --> 00:17:04,641
Bangalores up the line!
Bangalores up the line!

117
00:17:04,725 --> 00:17:07,018
Heads up! Bangers coming your way!

118
00:17:07,103 --> 00:17:09,521
Come on, come on, come on!

119
00:17:09,605 --> 00:17:12,440
- Jackson here, sir!
- Reiben back, sir!

120
00:17:13,109 --> 00:17:15,860
SOLDIER: Oh, my God!

121
00:17:18,864 --> 00:17:21,324
One more. Give me one more.

122
00:17:22,410 --> 00:17:24,202
(SOLDIER YELLING)

123
00:17:26,664 --> 00:17:29,374
Oh, my God, it hurts! I'm gonna die!

124
00:17:29,458 --> 00:17:33,420
Oh, my God! Oh, Jesus! Oh, my God!

125
00:17:34,547 --> 00:17:37,966
Keep it moving. Keep it moving.
Almost got it.

126
00:17:38,050 --> 00:17:41,094
- Jesus! Lucky bastard.
- Come on.

127
00:17:41,971 --> 00:17:44,264
- Move it!
- Keep it moving. You got it?

128
00:17:44,348 --> 00:17:47,392
SOLDIER: God! God, help me!

129
00:17:48,019 --> 00:17:49,936
You're not gonna die.
You're not gonna die.

130
00:17:50,021 --> 00:17:53,189
You're fine. Don't look at it.
Don't look at it.

131
00:17:53,274 --> 00:17:57,027
Bangalores! Clear the shingle!

132
00:17:57,111 --> 00:17:59,779
- Fire in the hole!
- Fire in the hole!

133
00:17:59,864 --> 00:18:02,407
Fire in the hole!

134
00:18:03,576 --> 00:18:05,327
Fire in the hole!

135
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:18,632
We're in business! Defilade!
Other side of the hole!

136
00:18:31,687 --> 00:18:34,022
SENIOR MEDIC: That's it! Let's go!

137
00:18:37,485 --> 00:18:39,611
Inspected. Morphine.

138
00:18:42,490 --> 00:18:43,865
Routine.

139
00:18:49,872 --> 00:18:51,331
Priority.

140
00:18:55,336 --> 00:18:56,544
He's gone.

141
00:18:59,715 --> 00:19:01,925
(MACHINE GUN FIRING
CONTINUOUSLY)

142
00:19:08,974 --> 00:19:10,725
Son of a...

143
00:19:11,477 --> 00:19:14,145
- Get in there.
- Fuck. I can't move.

144
00:19:14,230 --> 00:19:15,480
- Mellish.
- Yes, sir.

145
00:19:15,564 --> 00:19:17,399
Give me your bayonet.

146
00:19:29,954 --> 00:19:31,329
(EXPLOSION)

147
00:19:37,586 --> 00:19:41,339
Two MG42s and two mortars.
Add 20, left 30.

148
00:19:44,427 --> 00:19:47,178
There's a little defilade over there,
but it's the perfect fire position

149
00:19:47,263 --> 00:19:49,013
if we get some goddamn armour
on the beach.

150
00:19:49,098 --> 00:19:52,183
We gotta open up this draw!
We gotta get this draw open.

151
00:19:52,268 --> 00:19:54,185
Reiben, Mellish, let's get into the war!

152
00:19:54,270 --> 00:19:57,272
Grab some cover
and put some fire on that crew.

153
00:19:57,356 --> 00:20:01,067
Davis, Debernardo,
Young, Valk, get ready.

154
00:20:03,404 --> 00:20:05,113
Covering fire!

155
00:20:08,451 --> 00:20:10,160
MILLER: Go, go, go!

156
00:20:24,175 --> 00:20:26,134
Goddamn firing squad.

157
00:20:26,260 --> 00:20:29,429
It's the only way we can get
everybody the hell out of here.

158
00:20:29,513 --> 00:20:33,725
Short, Payton, McDonald, Parkes!
You're next!

159
00:20:33,809 --> 00:20:36,436
Why don't we just hand out
blindfolds, Cap?

160
00:20:36,520 --> 00:20:38,104
All we can do here is die.

161
00:20:38,189 --> 00:20:39,773
Covering fire!

162
00:20:42,276 --> 00:20:44,027
Go, go, go!

163
00:20:45,279 --> 00:20:46,988
Come on! Come on! Come on!

164
00:20:47,114 --> 00:20:48,990
Go, God damn it!

165
00:21:01,337 --> 00:21:04,005
- Jackson.
- Sir.

166
00:21:05,216 --> 00:21:06,800
- Do you see that impact crater?
- Yes, sir.

167
00:21:06,884 --> 00:21:09,260
That should give you complete defilade
from that machine-gun position.

168
00:21:09,345 --> 00:21:11,221
Get in there and give me
some fire discipline.

169
00:21:11,347 --> 00:21:13,223
Wait for my command.

170
00:21:18,979 --> 00:21:20,355
Go!

171
00:21:31,408 --> 00:21:34,702
Captain, if your mother saw you do that,
she'd be very upset.

172
00:21:34,829 --> 00:21:37,080
I thought you were my mother.

173
00:21:37,915 --> 00:21:40,667
Be not thou far from me, O Lord.

174
00:21:45,214 --> 00:21:49,217
O my God, I am heartily sorry
for having offended thee.

175
00:21:50,427 --> 00:21:52,679
I detest my sins
for having offended thee, O Lord.

176
00:21:52,763 --> 00:21:54,305
I detest my sins for having
offended thee, O Lord.

177
00:21:54,390 --> 00:21:55,723
Listen to me, Lord.

178
00:21:55,850 --> 00:21:57,559
(PRAYING IN LATIN)

179
00:22:01,689 --> 00:22:05,275
All my strength, haste thee to help me.

180
00:22:21,083 --> 00:22:26,087
- Dog One exit! Right here!
- We're in business!

181
00:22:27,631 --> 00:22:29,340
Move! Move!

182
00:23:10,799 --> 00:23:12,425
- Reiben.
- MILLER: Let's go, Sarge. Go!

183
00:23:12,509 --> 00:23:13,801
Reiben.

184
00:23:38,661 --> 00:23:41,120
SOLDIER: The place is full of 'em!

185
00:23:42,665 --> 00:23:44,332
MILLER: Come on, Doyle!

186
00:23:45,834 --> 00:23:47,251
Sarge?

187
00:23:52,591 --> 00:23:55,677
- Flame!
- Doyle, do it!

188
00:24:00,182 --> 00:24:02,850
Don't shoot! Let them burn!

189
00:24:19,785 --> 00:24:21,786
(SURRENDERING IN GERMAN)

190
00:24:24,832 --> 00:24:28,126
SOLDIER 1: I'll give you "comrade,"
you son of a bitch!

191
00:24:28,210 --> 00:24:29,877
SOLDIER 2: Lie down!

192
00:24:58,073 --> 00:25:00,575
Cease fire! Cease fire!

193
00:25:00,659 --> 00:25:03,828
Cut it out! Cut it out! Cease fire!

194
00:25:04,913 --> 00:25:06,581
Sugar Cane. Sugar Charlie 3.

195
00:25:06,707 --> 00:25:09,917
Say again, Dog One is open.
Send in the dozers.

196
00:25:10,044 --> 00:25:11,919
I'm waiting for you
to tie in my flanks. Over.

197
00:25:12,004 --> 00:25:13,796
(SPEAKING CZECH)

198
00:25:14,089 --> 00:25:15,548
What?

199
00:25:15,632 --> 00:25:17,675
(SPEAKING CZECH)

200
00:25:18,177 --> 00:25:21,512
What? I'm sorry, I can't understand
what you're saying.

201
00:25:29,438 --> 00:25:32,023
What did he say? What did he say?

202
00:25:32,107 --> 00:25:35,276
"Look, I washed for supper."

203
00:25:39,907 --> 00:25:41,407
God damn it!

204
00:25:47,790 --> 00:25:49,373
- Hey, Fish.
- Yeah?

205
00:25:49,458 --> 00:25:52,126
Look at this. A Hitler Youth knife.

206
00:25:53,629 --> 00:25:56,798
And now
it's a Shabbat challah cutter, right?

207
00:26:00,385 --> 00:26:01,677
(MOANING)

208
00:26:06,725 --> 00:26:08,392
MILLER: Keep it moving!

209
00:26:16,985 --> 00:26:18,319
(SOBBING)

210
00:27:08,579 --> 00:27:10,454
HORVATH: That's quite a view.

211
00:27:11,415 --> 00:27:12,957
Yes, it is.

212
00:27:14,668 --> 00:27:16,210
Quite a view.

213
00:27:24,136 --> 00:27:26,304
(WAVES CRASHING)

214
00:28:39,670 --> 00:28:41,462
(TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

215
00:28:51,014 --> 00:28:53,182
MAN 1: "Dear Mr Brian Boyd,

216
00:28:53,267 --> 00:28:55,434
"no doubt by now you have
received full information..."

217
00:28:55,519 --> 00:28:57,728
MAN 2: "Dear Mrs Jensen..."
MAN 1: "... untimely death of your son."

218
00:28:57,813 --> 00:28:59,730
MAN 2: "... no words of mine
can ever relieve the grief..."

219
00:28:59,815 --> 00:29:02,108
MAN 3: "Our outfit
has felt his loss tremendously."

220
00:29:02,192 --> 00:29:04,944
MAN 4: "He was a fine soldier
and he believed very strongly in..."

221
00:29:05,028 --> 00:29:07,738
MAN 5: "It's no secret any more
that we were involved

222
00:29:07,823 --> 00:29:09,907
"in one of the most important
operations of this war."

223
00:29:09,992 --> 00:29:12,535
MAN 1: "Al was the one
who held us all together.

224
00:29:12,619 --> 00:29:13,869
"He was always the first to volunteer..."

225
00:29:13,954 --> 00:29:15,538
MAN 6: "... came to a clearing
near a road

226
00:29:15,622 --> 00:29:17,581
"where over 4,000 troops had passed..."

227
00:29:17,666 --> 00:29:19,875
MAN 7: "Your husband
served in a combat unit

228
00:29:19,960 --> 00:29:22,503
"whose dangerous duty
is to place itself..."

229
00:29:22,587 --> 00:29:25,715
MAN 8: "... which we all cherish
and hold so dear.

230
00:29:25,799 --> 00:29:29,510
"The loss of Lee and others like him
is a distinct blow to the regiment."

231
00:29:29,594 --> 00:29:30,886
MAN 9: "I fully understand your desire

232
00:29:30,971 --> 00:29:33,639
"to learn as much as possible
regarding the circumstances

233
00:29:33,724 --> 00:29:35,850
"leading to his death."

234
00:30:28,028 --> 00:30:29,779
Colonel, I've got something
you should know about.

235
00:30:29,863 --> 00:30:31,155
Yes.

236
00:30:33,158 --> 00:30:35,701
These two men died in Normandy.

237
00:30:36,328 --> 00:30:39,163
This one at Omaha Beach.

238
00:30:39,247 --> 00:30:42,708
- Sean Ryan.
- This man at Utah.

239
00:30:44,378 --> 00:30:46,087
Peter Ryan.

240
00:30:49,841 --> 00:30:52,927
This man was killed
last week in New Guinea.

241
00:30:55,680 --> 00:30:58,099
Daniel Ryan.

242
00:30:58,809 --> 00:31:00,726
The three men are brothers, sir.

243
00:31:00,811 --> 00:31:02,269
I've just learned that, this afternoon,

244
00:31:02,354 --> 00:31:06,148
their mother is going
to be getting all three telegrams.

245
00:31:09,111 --> 00:31:11,362
That's not all. There's a fourth brother.
The youngest.

246
00:31:11,446 --> 00:31:13,447
He parachuted in
with the 101 st Airborne,

247
00:31:13,532 --> 00:31:14,990
night before the invasion.

248
00:31:15,075 --> 00:31:16,909
He's somewhere in Normandy.
We don't know where.

249
00:31:16,993 --> 00:31:19,412
- Is he alive?
- We don't know.

250
00:31:23,583 --> 00:31:25,209
Come with me.

251
00:33:09,022 --> 00:33:11,398
MARSHALL: God damn it.

252
00:33:12,234 --> 00:33:14,068
All four of them
were in the same company

253
00:33:14,152 --> 00:33:16,153
in the 29th Division,
but we split them up

254
00:33:16,238 --> 00:33:18,030
after the Sullivan brothers died
on the Juneau.

255
00:33:18,823 --> 00:33:21,825
Any contact with the fourth son, James?

256
00:33:21,952 --> 00:33:25,913
No, sir. He was dropped about
15 miles inland near Neuville.

257
00:33:25,997 --> 00:33:27,289
But that's still deep
behind German lines.

258
00:33:27,374 --> 00:33:29,583
Now, Mac,
there is no way you can know

259
00:33:29,668 --> 00:33:32,586
where in the hell he was dropped.

260
00:33:32,671 --> 00:33:34,630
General, first reports out of
Ike's people at SHAEF

261
00:33:34,714 --> 00:33:36,590
said the 101 st is scattered
all to hell and gone.

262
00:33:36,675 --> 00:33:39,051
There's misdrops all over Normandy.

263
00:33:39,135 --> 00:33:42,054
Now, assuming Private Ryan
even survived the jump,

264
00:33:42,138 --> 00:33:43,597
he could be anywhere.

265
00:33:43,682 --> 00:33:45,724
In fact, he's probably KIA.

266
00:33:45,809 --> 00:33:49,478
And frankly, sir, we go sending
some sort of rescue mission,

267
00:33:49,563 --> 00:33:52,147
flathatting throughout swarms
of German reinforcements

268
00:33:52,232 --> 00:33:56,068
all along our axis of advance,
they're gonna be KIA, too.

269
00:34:18,592 --> 00:34:20,634
I have a letter here,

270
00:34:22,012 --> 00:34:26,098
written a long time ago
to a Mrs Bixby in Boston.

271
00:34:26,182 --> 00:34:28,100
So bear with me.

272
00:34:30,937 --> 00:34:32,479
"Dear Madam,

273
00:34:33,189 --> 00:34:35,441
"I have been shown in the files
of the War Department

274
00:34:35,525 --> 00:34:39,278
"a statement of the Adjutant
General of Massachusetts

275
00:34:39,362 --> 00:34:42,698
"that you are the mother of five

276
00:34:45,702 --> 00:34:49,413
"sons who have died gloriously
on the field of battle.

277
00:34:52,083 --> 00:34:55,836
"I feel how weak and fruitless
must be any words of mine

278
00:34:56,630 --> 00:35:00,007
"that would attempt
to beguile you from the grief

279
00:35:00,425 --> 00:35:02,843
"of a loss so overwhelming.

280
00:35:04,679 --> 00:35:06,680
"But I cannot refrain
from tendering to you

281
00:35:06,765 --> 00:35:09,933
"the consolation that may be found

282
00:35:10,018 --> 00:35:14,271
"in the thanks of the republic
they died to save.

283
00:35:18,443 --> 00:35:19,735
"I pray that Our Heavenly Father

284
00:35:19,819 --> 00:35:22,905
"may assuage the anguish
of your bereavement

285
00:35:22,989 --> 00:35:27,368
"and leave you only the cherished
memory of the loved lost,

286
00:35:28,495 --> 00:35:30,120
"and the solemn pride
that must be yours

287
00:35:30,205 --> 00:35:34,500
"to have laid so costly a sacrifice
upon the altar of freedom.

288
00:35:35,085 --> 00:35:38,253
"Yours very sincerely and respectfully,

289
00:35:38,338 --> 00:35:40,172
"Abraham Lincoln."

290
00:35:59,025 --> 00:36:00,859
That boy is alive.

291
00:36:01,569 --> 00:36:04,488
We are gonna send somebody
to find him,

292
00:36:05,615 --> 00:36:08,784
and we are gonna get him
the hell out of there.

293
00:36:09,828 --> 00:36:11,495
OFFICER 1: Yes, sir.
OFFICER 2: Yes, sir.

294
00:36:24,175 --> 00:36:26,635
We expected 32 tanks to float to
the beach. Twenty-seven didn't make it.

295
00:36:26,720 --> 00:36:28,762
- Miller, Charlie Company.
- Go on in, Captain.

296
00:36:28,847 --> 00:36:29,972
I understand your situation.

297
00:36:30,056 --> 00:36:33,142
But if we don't offload
those duel-drive Shermans by 0600,

298
00:36:33,226 --> 00:36:34,435
we're gonna have an entire division

299
00:36:34,519 --> 00:36:38,230
stuck at Carentan
with its pants around its ankles.

300
00:36:38,314 --> 00:36:40,733
Well, you let me know then.

301
00:36:40,817 --> 00:36:43,694
Have Charlie Company hold at Vierville
until we can get some armour up there.

302
00:36:43,778 --> 00:36:45,612
SOLDIER: Yes, sir. Runner!

303
00:36:52,078 --> 00:36:54,830
Airborne was supposed to win
an open door for the rest of us.

304
00:36:54,914 --> 00:36:57,499
Instead they misdropped,
scattered all their sticks into the wind.

305
00:36:57,584 --> 00:37:01,754
- What's your situation?
- Yes, sir. Sector four is secure.

306
00:37:02,130 --> 00:37:03,380
We...

307
00:37:03,965 --> 00:37:09,052
We took out towed 88s
here, here and here.

308
00:37:09,137 --> 00:37:10,804
They'd already gotten four
of our Shermans

309
00:37:10,889 --> 00:37:12,181
and a number
of our deuce and a halves.

310
00:37:12,265 --> 00:37:15,225
These two minefields
are actually one big one.

311
00:37:15,310 --> 00:37:16,977
We tried to make our way up
through the middle of it,

312
00:37:17,061 --> 00:37:19,438
but it turned into a mixed,
high-density field,

313
00:37:19,522 --> 00:37:20,647
little bit of everything.

314
00:37:20,732 --> 00:37:24,568
Spreng Mine 44s. Schuh Mine 42s,
pot mines. A-200s,

315
00:37:24,652 --> 00:37:28,155
the little wooden bastards
that the mine detectors don't pick up.

316
00:37:28,239 --> 00:37:32,701
This road here, they placed
big mushrooms, Teller Mine 43s,

317
00:37:32,786 --> 00:37:33,952
I guess for our tanks,

318
00:37:34,037 --> 00:37:37,539
from here right up
to the edge of the village. Right here.

319
00:37:37,624 --> 00:37:39,583
So we marked them,
called the engineers.

320
00:37:39,667 --> 00:37:40,959
Resistance?

321
00:37:41,044 --> 00:37:43,253
We had higher
support expectations, sir.

322
00:37:43,338 --> 00:37:45,631
There was an under-strength
company without artillery.

323
00:37:45,715 --> 00:37:48,967
Wehrmacht 346 Infantry,
Von Luck Kampfgruppe.

324
00:37:49,052 --> 00:37:51,094
We ended up with 23 prisoners.

325
00:37:51,179 --> 00:37:54,348
We turned them over
to MPs from the 29th.

326
00:37:57,101 --> 00:37:59,394
What about our casualties?

327
00:38:00,021 --> 00:38:02,147
Well, the figures

328
00:38:03,525 --> 00:38:07,027
were 35 dead, times two wounded.

329
00:38:07,111 --> 00:38:10,364
They just didn't wanna
give up those 88s.

330
00:38:12,283 --> 00:38:15,035
It was a tough assignment.
That's why you got it.

331
00:38:15,119 --> 00:38:16,620
Yes, sir.

332
00:38:17,872 --> 00:38:19,373
John...

333
00:38:22,335 --> 00:38:24,253
I've got another one for you.

334
00:38:24,337 --> 00:38:27,297
- Yes, sir.
- This one's straight from the top.

335
00:38:33,888 --> 00:38:36,056
MILLER: You and I are taking a squad
over to Neuville

336
00:38:36,140 --> 00:38:38,058
on a public-relations mission.

337
00:38:38,142 --> 00:38:39,977
HORVATH: You leading a squad?

338
00:38:40,061 --> 00:38:43,188
MILLER: Some private in the 101 st
lost three brothers,

339
00:38:43,273 --> 00:38:44,940
and he's got a ticket home.

340
00:38:45,024 --> 00:38:46,149
HORVATH: How come Neuville?

341
00:38:46,234 --> 00:38:47,442
MILLER: They think
he's up there somewhere,

342
00:38:47,527 --> 00:38:50,153
part of all those airborne misdrops.

343
00:38:50,238 --> 00:38:52,948
HORVATH: It's not gonna be easy
finding one particular soldier

344
00:38:53,032 --> 00:38:54,199
in the middle of this
whole goddamn war.

345
00:38:54,284 --> 00:38:56,743
Like finding a needle
in a stack of needles.

346
00:38:56,828 --> 00:38:58,412
But what about the company?

347
00:38:58,496 --> 00:39:01,790
We take the pick of the litter
and the rest get folded into Baker.

348
00:39:01,875 --> 00:39:03,584
Jesus Christ.

349
00:39:03,668 --> 00:39:05,711
They took away your company?

350
00:39:05,795 --> 00:39:10,299
It wasn't my company. It was
the Army's. So they told me, anyway.

351
00:39:10,425 --> 00:39:14,344
Give me Reiben on BAR, Jackson,
Wade, Beasley and Caparzo.

352
00:39:14,429 --> 00:39:15,846
Beasley's dead.

353
00:39:15,930 --> 00:39:18,724
All right, Mellish, then.
We got anybody speaks French?

354
00:39:18,808 --> 00:39:22,644
- Not that I know of.
- What about Talbot?

355
00:39:22,770 --> 00:39:25,772
- This morning.
- Oh. All right.

356
00:39:26,190 --> 00:39:28,275
I'm gonna go try to dig up
another interpreter.

357
00:39:28,359 --> 00:39:30,110
Assemble at battalion motor pool
on the beach.

358
00:39:30,194 --> 00:39:31,278
Yes, sir.

359
00:39:31,362 --> 00:39:32,738
- Sarge, what we gonna do?
- Okay, listen up...

360
00:39:32,822 --> 00:39:34,197
- What?
- What are we gonna do?

361
00:39:34,282 --> 00:39:35,991
You're going home wrapped
in an American flag

362
00:39:36,117 --> 00:39:38,118
with a hunk of cheese
in your ass, Caparzo, you smart ass.

363
00:39:38,202 --> 00:39:39,953
- Now, listen up.
- I thought you liked it in the ass.

364
00:39:40,038 --> 00:39:41,371
- What?
- I thought you liked it in the ass.

365
00:39:42,040 --> 00:39:44,166
Attention!

366
00:39:44,292 --> 00:39:45,500
As you were.

367
00:39:45,627 --> 00:39:47,669
I'm looking
for Corporal Upham, Timothy E.

368
00:39:47,795 --> 00:39:49,087
Yes, sir. I'm Upham, sir.

369
00:39:49,172 --> 00:39:50,797
I understand you speak
French and German.

370
00:39:50,882 --> 00:39:52,674
- Yes, sir.
- How's your accent?

371
00:39:52,800 --> 00:39:54,426
Just a slight one in French,
but my German's clean.

372
00:39:54,510 --> 00:39:56,178
- Has a touch of Bavarian, sir.
- Very good.

373
00:39:56,304 --> 00:39:57,846
You've been reassigned to me.
Grab your gear.

374
00:39:57,972 --> 00:40:00,307
- We're going to a place called Neuville.
- Yes, sir.

375
00:40:00,391 --> 00:40:02,559
- When was this updated?
- Updated as of 0830 hour this morning.

376
00:40:02,644 --> 00:40:04,895
- Sir...
- This is the 12th SS Panzer.

377
00:40:04,979 --> 00:40:06,813
These are the two axes
that advance south.

378
00:40:06,898 --> 00:40:09,358
- Sir, there are Germans in Neuville.
- There are artillery up here, sir.

379
00:40:09,484 --> 00:40:12,152
- That's what I understand. Corporal.
- Yes, sir.

380
00:40:12,236 --> 00:40:14,404
Sir, there are a lot
of Germans in Neuville.

381
00:40:14,489 --> 00:40:15,572
You have a problem with that, Corporal?

382
00:40:15,657 --> 00:40:18,116
No, sir. Just if you consider
I've never been in combat, sir.

383
00:40:18,201 --> 00:40:19,826
I make maps and I translate.
And that's...

384
00:40:19,911 --> 00:40:22,829
I need someone who speaks
French and German.

385
00:40:22,914 --> 00:40:24,665
- Yes, sir.
- My two guys were killed.

386
00:40:24,749 --> 00:40:27,417
Yes, sir. It's just that I haven't
held a weapon since basic training, sir.

387
00:40:27,502 --> 00:40:30,128
Did you fire the weapon
in basic training?

388
00:40:30,213 --> 00:40:31,421
Yes, sir.

389
00:40:31,506 --> 00:40:34,257
- Well, then, get your gear.
- Yes, sir.

390
00:40:35,385 --> 00:40:37,678
Sir, may I bring...

391
00:40:41,432 --> 00:40:43,934
May I bring my typewriter, sir?

392
00:40:49,023 --> 00:40:50,357
Yes, sir.

393
00:40:53,611 --> 00:40:55,404
Thank you very much, sir.

394
00:40:55,530 --> 00:40:57,864
- That a souvenir?
- No, sir.

395
00:40:57,949 --> 00:41:00,117
Take your time, Corporal.

396
00:41:04,455 --> 00:41:06,999
You should look
on the bright side of things, Corporal.

397
00:41:07,083 --> 00:41:08,208
Yes, sir.

398
00:41:08,292 --> 00:41:11,336
For one thing,
you don't need to carry those.

399
00:41:11,421 --> 00:41:14,381
- You'll need that.
- I'll need that, sir. Yes, sir.

400
00:41:59,927 --> 00:42:01,553
(SHEEP BLEATING)

401
00:42:06,934 --> 00:42:08,685
(BELL COLLARS RING)

402
00:42:12,940 --> 00:42:14,024
Hey!

403
00:42:14,442 --> 00:42:16,610
You want your head blown off,
you fancy little fuck?

404
00:42:16,694 --> 00:42:18,987
Don't you ever fucking touch me
with those little rat claws again.

405
00:42:19,113 --> 00:42:21,615
Get the fuck back in formation.

406
00:42:22,992 --> 00:42:26,495
I was just wondering
where you're from, that's...

407
00:42:31,542 --> 00:42:33,960
- Caparzo, is it?
- Hey, drop dead, Corporal.

408
00:42:34,045 --> 00:42:35,170
Got you.

409
00:42:35,296 --> 00:42:37,464
And another thing.
Every time you salute the captain,

410
00:42:37,548 --> 00:42:39,758
you make him a target for the Germans.

411
00:42:39,842 --> 00:42:41,635
So do us a favour. Don't do it.

412
00:42:41,719 --> 00:42:44,679
Especially when I'm standing
next to him, capisci?

413
00:42:45,515 --> 00:42:47,808
Corporal, what's your book about?

414
00:42:47,892 --> 00:42:49,601
- Hey. Watch your rifle.
- Sorry.

415
00:42:49,685 --> 00:42:50,936
Actually, it's about the...

416
00:42:51,020 --> 00:42:52,479
It's supposed to be about
the bonds of brotherhood

417
00:42:52,563 --> 00:42:54,481
that develop between
soldiers during war.

418
00:42:54,565 --> 00:42:56,650
Brotherhood?

419
00:42:56,734 --> 00:42:58,318
What do you know about brotherhood?

420
00:42:58,402 --> 00:43:00,529
Get a load of this guy, Fish.

421
00:43:00,655 --> 00:43:03,615
Why don't you ask
the captain where he's from?

422
00:43:03,699 --> 00:43:08,078
Yeah, ask the captain. He'll tell you
everything you wanna know about him.

423
00:43:08,246 --> 00:43:10,330
You wanna explain
the math of this to me?

424
00:43:10,414 --> 00:43:12,707
I mean, where's the sense
of risking the lives of the eight of us

425
00:43:12,834 --> 00:43:14,376
to save one guy.

426
00:43:14,502 --> 00:43:17,629
Twenty degrees.
Anybody wanna answer that?

427
00:43:17,713 --> 00:43:21,258
Reiben, think about
the poor bastard's mother.

428
00:43:21,342 --> 00:43:23,135
Hey, doc. I got a mother, all right?

429
00:43:23,219 --> 00:43:25,762
I mean, you got a mother.
Sarge has got a mother.

430
00:43:25,847 --> 00:43:29,516
I mean, shit, I bet even
the captain's got a mother.

431
00:43:29,600 --> 00:43:32,435
Well, maybe not the captain,
but the rest of us got mothers.

432
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:34,938
"Theirs not to reason why
Theirs but to do and die"

433
00:43:35,022 --> 00:43:36,857
(MELLISH VOCALISING)

434
00:43:37,567 --> 00:43:39,359
What the fuck is that
supposed to mean, Corporal, huh?

435
00:43:39,443 --> 00:43:41,111
We're all supposed to die. Is that it?

436
00:43:41,195 --> 00:43:43,947
Upham's talking about
our duty as soldiers.

437
00:43:44,031 --> 00:43:46,533
- Yes, sir.
- We all have orders we have to follow.

438
00:43:46,617 --> 00:43:49,327
And that supersedes everything,
including your mothers.

439
00:43:49,412 --> 00:43:50,996
Yes, sir. Thank you, sir.

440
00:43:51,080 --> 00:43:53,498
Even if you think
the mission's FUBAR, sir?

441
00:43:53,583 --> 00:43:56,585
Especially if you think
the mission's FUBAR.

442
00:43:56,711 --> 00:44:00,380
- What's FUBAR?
- Oh, it's German. Yeah.

443
00:44:00,965 --> 00:44:03,049
Never heard of that.

444
00:44:03,134 --> 00:44:06,428
Sir, I have an opinion on this matter.

445
00:44:07,221 --> 00:44:10,140
Well, by all means,
share it with the squad.

446
00:44:10,224 --> 00:44:12,434
Well, from my way of thinking, sir,

447
00:44:12,560 --> 00:44:14,895
this entire mission
is a serious misallocation

448
00:44:14,979 --> 00:44:17,397
of valuable military resources.

449
00:44:17,481 --> 00:44:19,399
Yeah. Go on.

450
00:44:19,483 --> 00:44:21,943
Well, it seems to me, sir,
that God gave me a special gift,

451
00:44:22,069 --> 00:44:25,322
made me a fine instrument of warfare.

452
00:44:25,406 --> 00:44:28,116
Reiben, pay attention.
Now, this is the way to gripe!

453
00:44:28,242 --> 00:44:29,492
Continue, Jackson.

454
00:44:29,577 --> 00:44:31,453
Well, what I mean by that, sir,

455
00:44:31,579 --> 00:44:34,247
is if you was to put me
and this here sniper rifle anywhere,

456
00:44:34,332 --> 00:44:37,083
up to and including one mile
of Adolf Hitler

457
00:44:37,168 --> 00:44:38,877
with a clear line of sight, sir...

458
00:44:38,961 --> 00:44:41,838
Pack your bags, fellas.
War's over. Amen.

459
00:44:41,923 --> 00:44:44,216
Oh, that's brilliant, bumpkin.

460
00:44:44,300 --> 00:44:47,344
So, Captain, what about you?
I mean, you don't gripe at all?

461
00:44:47,428 --> 00:44:49,846
I don't gripe to you, Reiben.
I'm a captain.

462
00:44:49,931 --> 00:44:52,849
There's a chain of command.
Gripes go up, not down. Always up.

463
00:44:52,934 --> 00:44:54,226
You gripe to me,

464
00:44:54,310 --> 00:44:57,854
I gripe to my superior officers,
so on, so on and so on.

465
00:44:57,939 --> 00:44:59,731
I don't gripe to you.
I don't gripe in front of you.

466
00:44:59,815 --> 00:45:01,816
You should know that as a Ranger.

467
00:45:01,943 --> 00:45:03,777
I'm sorry, sir, but...

468
00:45:03,861 --> 00:45:06,696
Let's say you weren't a captain,
or maybe I was a major.

469
00:45:06,781 --> 00:45:08,573
What would you say then?

470
00:45:08,658 --> 00:45:10,450
Well, in that case,

471
00:45:10,534 --> 00:45:12,619
I'd say this is an excellent mission, sir,

472
00:45:12,703 --> 00:45:15,830
with an extremely
valuable objective, sir,

473
00:45:15,957 --> 00:45:17,374
worthy of my best efforts, sir.

474
00:45:17,458 --> 00:45:22,963
Moreover, I feel heartfelt sorrow
for the mother of Private James Ryan,

475
00:45:23,047 --> 00:45:26,591
and am willing to lay down my life
and the lives of my men,

476
00:45:26,676 --> 00:45:30,136
especially you, Reiben,
to ease her suffering.

477
00:45:31,639 --> 00:45:33,640
- He's good.
- I love him.

478
00:45:33,891 --> 00:45:35,976
(BOTH MAKE KISSING SOUNDS)

479
00:45:44,318 --> 00:45:45,694
Right.

480
00:45:56,497 --> 00:45:58,331
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

481
00:45:58,416 --> 00:46:00,083
(DISTANT GUNFIRE)

482
00:46:19,520 --> 00:46:21,813
(VILLAGERS SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

483
00:46:27,570 --> 00:46:30,780
- Thunder!
- SOLDIER: Flash!

484
00:46:30,865 --> 00:46:34,117
Upham, over there. Reiben, you four go.

485
00:46:37,580 --> 00:46:40,248
(MAN SPEAKING ON LOUDSPEAKER)

486
00:46:43,586 --> 00:46:45,628
REIBEN: Go, go, go, go, go!

487
00:46:50,968 --> 00:46:53,928
- You guys are a sight for sore eyes.
- Sergeant Hill, our relief showed up.

488
00:46:54,013 --> 00:46:55,805
How many are you?

489
00:46:55,890 --> 00:46:58,516
MILLER: Just eight of us.
We're not your relief. Sorry.

490
00:46:58,601 --> 00:47:00,143
You're not the relief,
what do you mean, sir?

491
00:47:00,227 --> 00:47:01,811
We're here for a Private Ryan.

492
00:47:01,896 --> 00:47:04,439
Who? Ryan? What for?

493
00:47:04,523 --> 00:47:05,648
- Is he here?
- Well, I don't know.

494
00:47:05,733 --> 00:47:08,026
Maybe with a mixed unit
on the other side of town.

495
00:47:08,110 --> 00:47:10,195
It's hard to get to. The Germans
punched a hole in our centre

496
00:47:10,279 --> 00:47:12,155
a few hours ago,
they cut us right in two.

497
00:47:12,239 --> 00:47:15,742
- What's his name again?
- Ryan. James Ryan.

498
00:47:15,826 --> 00:47:17,202
He dropped in with 101 st.

499
00:47:17,286 --> 00:47:20,246
- Goldman, get me a runner up here.
- Runner!

500
00:47:20,331 --> 00:47:21,998
Come on.

501
00:47:25,961 --> 00:47:28,546
Jonesy, make a hole up there!

502
00:47:30,091 --> 00:47:33,218
We got stopped by some intense
rifle action from the eastward.

503
00:47:33,302 --> 00:47:37,013
The Germans have been
reinforcing two regiments all day.

504
00:47:37,098 --> 00:47:39,307
The streets have been quiet
for about 45 minutes.

505
00:47:39,392 --> 00:47:41,893
Most of the German fire now
is concentrated to the westward.

506
00:47:41,977 --> 00:47:43,186
Who's that on the loudspeaker?

507
00:47:43,270 --> 00:47:45,271
That? That's Dagwood Dusseldorf,

508
00:47:45,356 --> 00:47:47,190
our friendly neighbourhood
morale officer.

509
00:47:47,274 --> 00:47:50,276
DUSSELDORF: The Statue of Liberty
is kaput.

510
00:47:50,361 --> 00:47:53,738
- "The Statue of Liberty is kaput."
- DUSSELDORF:... kaput.

511
00:47:53,823 --> 00:47:55,615
That's disconcerting.

512
00:47:58,661 --> 00:48:00,245
HILL: Take the second left...

513
00:48:00,329 --> 00:48:03,623
Your father was circumcised
by my rabbi, you prick!

514
00:48:03,707 --> 00:48:06,793
HILL: Private Ryan, James,
probably misdropped with the 101.

515
00:48:06,877 --> 00:48:08,837
- Got that?
- Cover!

516
00:48:08,921 --> 00:48:10,839
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

517
00:48:16,512 --> 00:48:17,929
Go!

518
00:48:22,268 --> 00:48:24,102
(BULLETS WHIZZING BY)

519
00:48:41,912 --> 00:48:44,122
- You sadistic fucking animals!
- Get down.

520
00:48:44,206 --> 00:48:47,292
They know we're not in direct contact.
They're gonna single out the runners.

521
00:48:47,376 --> 00:48:49,085
Yeah. Why do they
keep shooting him up like that?

522
00:48:49,170 --> 00:48:51,796
Long as his lungs have breath in them,
he still carries the message.

523
00:48:51,881 --> 00:48:53,590
- We'd do the same thing.
- No, we wouldn't!

524
00:48:53,674 --> 00:48:56,634
- Wade! Get them ready to travel.
- Yes, sir.

525
00:48:56,719 --> 00:48:58,595
- HILL: Boyd!
- Come on!

526
00:48:58,679 --> 00:49:01,431
Try again. See if you can let
Captain Hamill know we're coming.

527
00:49:01,515 --> 00:49:04,100
What's the rest of Neuville look like?

528
00:49:04,185 --> 00:49:06,561
Next block's got two-storey buildings,
both sides of the street.

529
00:49:06,645 --> 00:49:08,021
- There's a lot of windows.
- ... copy? Over.

530
00:49:08,105 --> 00:49:10,482
And then there's a wide open square
with pretty good cover on the left.

531
00:49:10,566 --> 00:49:12,817
- Show me.
- Sarge, hold right here.

532
00:49:12,902 --> 00:49:14,319
Yes, sir!

533
00:49:18,741 --> 00:49:21,367
All right. Let's stay out of this enfilade
and use the buildings.

534
00:49:21,452 --> 00:49:22,577
Try a left hook.

535
00:49:22,661 --> 00:49:24,412
Shoot and scoot,
two of yours, two of mine.

536
00:49:24,497 --> 00:49:26,956
Hastings, Goldman, up front!

537
00:49:28,125 --> 00:49:30,919
- Reiben, Caparzo. Fundamentals.
- They're still jamming us.

538
00:49:31,003 --> 00:49:33,630
Short runs. High and low at the corners.

539
00:49:33,714 --> 00:49:36,174
It's gonna be tight.
Be prepared for close contact.

540
00:49:36,258 --> 00:49:38,092
- Go. Upham.
- Yes, sir.

541
00:49:38,177 --> 00:49:40,303
- You stay with Sergeant Horvath.
- Stay right here.

542
00:49:40,387 --> 00:49:44,015
I'll wear him like underwear, Captain!
Stay with me.

543
00:49:52,149 --> 00:49:53,608
All right, past the end
of the block to the left.

544
00:49:53,692 --> 00:49:54,817
Those are the gates to the square.

545
00:49:54,902 --> 00:49:56,194
Good.

546
00:50:04,203 --> 00:50:05,995
Reiben, where's the captain from?

547
00:50:06,080 --> 00:50:08,248
You figure that one out,
you got yourself a nice prize.

548
00:50:08,332 --> 00:50:09,958
300 bucks, last I heard.

549
00:50:10,042 --> 00:50:13,294
Company's got a pool.
5 bucks gets you in.

550
00:50:17,716 --> 00:50:19,050
Easy.

551
00:50:20,636 --> 00:50:24,514
It's around this corner.
Defilade right up to those gates.

552
00:50:25,683 --> 00:50:28,101
Somebody must know where he's from,
what he did for a living.

553
00:50:28,185 --> 00:50:30,019
I've been with him
since Kasserine Pass,

554
00:50:30,104 --> 00:50:31,271
but I don't have a clue.

555
00:50:31,355 --> 00:50:33,147
My ankles are killing me.

556
00:50:33,232 --> 00:50:36,192
I'll need a wheelchair
before this war is over.

557
00:50:36,277 --> 00:50:38,736
Oh, that's it. Oh, my God.

558
00:50:38,821 --> 00:50:42,073
Got ankles like an old woman.
Like an old...

559
00:50:42,157 --> 00:50:43,866
Oh, God.

560
00:50:45,619 --> 00:50:48,788
Reiben, so, you don't even know
where he went to school?

561
00:50:48,872 --> 00:50:50,081
Captain didn't go to school.

562
00:50:50,165 --> 00:50:53,334
They assembled him at OCS
out of spare body parts of dead Gls.

563
00:50:53,419 --> 00:50:54,794
You gotta pay attention to detail.

564
00:50:54,878 --> 00:50:56,796
I know exactly where he's from
and exactly what he did

565
00:50:56,880 --> 00:50:59,132
'cause I pay attention to detail.

566
00:50:59,216 --> 00:51:02,677
Hey, Upham,
careful you don't step in the bullshit.

567
00:51:08,017 --> 00:51:10,393
- Do it.
- Thunder!

568
00:51:10,477 --> 00:51:13,104
Thunder, or we will fire on you!

569
00:51:13,188 --> 00:51:14,981
(SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

570
00:51:22,990 --> 00:51:24,907
Upham, tell them to show themselves.

571
00:51:24,992 --> 00:51:27,994
(SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

572
00:51:33,459 --> 00:51:34,959
(BABY CRYING)

573
00:51:35,169 --> 00:51:37,545
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

574
00:51:37,713 --> 00:51:39,172
Ask them if they know
where the Germans are.

575
00:51:39,256 --> 00:51:41,174
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

576
00:51:44,887 --> 00:51:47,764
- What's he saying?
- UPHAM: Something about the children.

577
00:51:48,807 --> 00:51:49,849
They want us to take the children.

578
00:51:49,933 --> 00:51:51,309
MILLER: No, no, no.
We can't take the kids.

579
00:51:51,393 --> 00:51:53,061
We can't take the kids. We can't!

580
00:51:53,145 --> 00:51:56,397
We can't take the kids! No!

581
00:51:59,276 --> 00:52:00,443
UPHAM: They think
they'll be safe with us.

582
00:52:00,527 --> 00:52:02,695
MILLER: It's not gonna be
safe when they're with us!

583
00:52:02,780 --> 00:52:06,824
- It's okay. It's okay.
- Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!

584
00:52:06,909 --> 00:52:10,703
- Are you nuts? Listen to the captain!
- They think they'll be safe with us, sir.

585
00:52:10,996 --> 00:52:14,290
MILLER: Caparzo! Put that kid back!

586
00:52:14,750 --> 00:52:16,042
CAPARZO: It's okay.

587
00:52:16,126 --> 00:52:19,379
- Caparzo! Put that little girl back!
- It's okay. It's okay. It's okay.

588
00:52:19,463 --> 00:52:22,507
Caparzo, give that kid back now!

589
00:52:22,591 --> 00:52:26,636
Upham, how do you say, "It's okay"?
I can't. She reminds me of my niece, sir.

590
00:52:26,720 --> 00:52:28,680
Caparzo, get the kid back up there!

591
00:52:28,764 --> 00:52:30,098
Captain, the decent thing to do

592
00:52:30,182 --> 00:52:32,392
is to at least take her down
the road to the next town.

593
00:52:32,476 --> 00:52:35,728
We're not here to do the decent thing!
We're here to follow fucking orders!

594
00:52:35,813 --> 00:52:38,189
Sarge, take this goddamn kid!

595
00:52:38,941 --> 00:52:41,109
Cover! Cover!

596
00:52:50,411 --> 00:52:53,329
REIBEN: God damn it!
Where'd that come from?

597
00:52:55,124 --> 00:52:58,584
He was on the ground
before we heard the shot.

598
00:53:03,340 --> 00:53:05,258
That's where I'd be.

599
00:53:07,136 --> 00:53:08,344
I didn't see it.

600
00:53:08,429 --> 00:53:11,264
Four hundred fifty yards, Captain.
Maybe a shade under.

601
00:53:11,348 --> 00:53:15,351
I wouldn't venture out there, fellas!
This sniper's got talent!

602
00:53:15,436 --> 00:53:16,686
Jacqueline!

603
00:53:16,770 --> 00:53:18,604
(SCREAMING IN FRENCH)

604
00:53:20,065 --> 00:53:23,526
Please don't cry. I'm gonna take you
back to your mama and papa.

605
00:53:23,610 --> 00:53:25,820
Please don't cry. Come on.

606
00:53:29,074 --> 00:53:30,491
MILLER: Carpy.

607
00:53:41,587 --> 00:53:43,921
- CAPARZO: Captain.
- Hold on, Caparzo.

608
00:53:45,340 --> 00:53:47,508
Help me up. I can walk. I can walk.

609
00:53:47,634 --> 00:53:49,761
Caparzo, stay still!

610
00:54:01,190 --> 00:54:03,483
Two clicks, left wind.

611
00:54:07,154 --> 00:54:08,488
Fish!

612
00:54:09,698 --> 00:54:11,657
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

613
00:54:11,784 --> 00:54:13,451
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

614
00:54:16,497 --> 00:54:19,290
Captain, can you see him
from there? How is he?

615
00:54:19,374 --> 00:54:21,334
Wade, you stay put.

616
00:54:21,460 --> 00:54:23,628
Where's he shot, Captain?

617
00:54:25,464 --> 00:54:28,007
- Captain, can you see him from there?
- You stay there!

618
00:54:28,133 --> 00:54:31,761
Damn it, stay down!
What's the matter with you?

619
00:54:31,845 --> 00:54:35,598
Am I gonna take care of you
if you get hit? Huh?

620
00:54:35,682 --> 00:54:38,935
- Fish, come over here.
- Carpy, put your head down.

621
00:54:39,019 --> 00:54:42,188
Why can't you put your head down?

622
00:54:49,863 --> 00:54:52,698
JACKSON: O my God, I trust in thee.

623
00:54:52,825 --> 00:54:54,826
Let me not be ashamed.

624
00:54:55,702 --> 00:54:58,538
Let not my enemies triumph over me.

625
00:55:08,340 --> 00:55:10,007
Copy it.

626
00:55:10,092 --> 00:55:12,426
Copy it and send it for me.

627
00:55:12,511 --> 00:55:14,971
Carpy, you're gonna send it yourself.
Put it down!

628
00:55:15,055 --> 00:55:18,349
- It's got blood!
- I see it. Carpy, I see it.

629
00:55:22,896 --> 00:55:27,024
It's to my dad. It's got blood on it, Fish.

630
00:55:55,053 --> 00:55:57,597
We got him. Stay down.

631
00:55:58,473 --> 00:56:00,600
(COUPLE SHOUTING IN FRENCH)

632
00:56:06,315 --> 00:56:10,526
- How bad is it?
- Chest, maybe lung shot.

633
00:56:15,324 --> 00:56:17,366
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

634
00:56:25,959 --> 00:56:28,502
Get that 30 up the street!

635
00:56:33,300 --> 00:56:34,550
MILLER: Detail!

636
00:56:34,635 --> 00:56:36,719
SOLDIER 1: Clear up!
SOLDIER 2: Clear down!

637
00:56:52,361 --> 00:56:55,279
That's why we can't take children.

638
00:57:01,328 --> 00:57:04,914
Sergeant Horvath, do an ammo check.

639
00:57:04,998 --> 00:57:08,668
Upham, canteens. Fill them up.

640
00:57:09,252 --> 00:57:11,045
- Sergeant Hill.
- Yes, sir.

641
00:57:11,129 --> 00:57:15,508
MILLER: Gather your men. We'll form up
at the northwest corner of the square.

642
00:57:15,592 --> 00:57:17,259
- Jackson!
- Sir.

643
00:57:17,344 --> 00:57:22,139
MILLER: Mellish, check the tower,
hustle back here. Right now. Go!

644
00:57:33,986 --> 00:57:35,611
Fuck Ryan.

645
00:57:46,123 --> 00:57:48,541
- Thunder!
- SOLDIER: Flash!

646
00:57:48,625 --> 00:57:50,167
Come on in.

647
00:57:54,965 --> 00:57:57,216
HILL: Hey, guys, we're looking
for Captain Hamill.

648
00:57:57,300 --> 00:57:59,051
Somewhere down there
across the square.

649
00:57:59,136 --> 00:58:00,428
HILL: Across the square.

650
00:58:00,512 --> 00:58:03,097
SOLDIER: Go easy. Watch for snipers.

651
00:58:03,682 --> 00:58:05,433
Sit down.

652
00:58:21,992 --> 00:58:24,577
Jimmy T, go find Captain Hamill,
bring him in here.

653
00:58:24,661 --> 00:58:25,995
What? Up there?

654
00:58:26,079 --> 00:58:28,831
How the hell should I know?
Would you go look, please?

655
00:58:28,915 --> 00:58:30,875
Thank you, you moron.

656
00:58:32,252 --> 00:58:33,836
All right.

657
00:58:33,920 --> 00:58:37,381
You guys just flake out here for a while.

658
00:58:39,342 --> 00:58:42,803
Let me get this goddamn
hitchhiker out of my boot.

659
00:58:45,849 --> 00:58:47,641
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

660
00:58:52,773 --> 00:58:54,607
Drop your weapons!
Drop your weapons!

661
00:58:54,691 --> 00:58:57,902
- Drop them now!
- Drop the fucking weapons!

662
00:59:00,739 --> 00:59:04,784
- I'll shoot you! I'll shoot you!
- Drop! Drop! Drop them!

663
00:59:07,287 --> 00:59:09,580
Now! Put them down!

664
00:59:11,041 --> 00:59:12,833
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

665
00:59:24,721 --> 00:59:26,138
Clear up!

666
00:59:31,436 --> 00:59:35,147
- Shit. Shit!
- HAMILL: Clear up!

667
00:59:36,608 --> 00:59:38,150
Clear down!

668
00:59:50,122 --> 00:59:53,874
- Enough to make you old.
- Let's hope so.

669
01:00:04,845 --> 01:00:06,345
Fred Hamill, Pathfinders, 101 st.

670
01:00:06,429 --> 01:00:09,390
John Miller, 2nd Rangers. Thank you.

671
01:00:11,309 --> 01:00:12,935
We're here looking
for a Private James Ryan.

672
01:00:13,019 --> 01:00:16,021
He's part of your outfit.
Any chance at all you policed him up?

673
01:00:16,731 --> 01:00:19,275
HAMILL: How was the road in?
MILLER: Scenic.

674
01:00:19,818 --> 01:00:23,529
- We lost most of our ammo.
- Not to mention one of our men.

675
01:00:24,030 --> 01:00:27,283
Lieutenant, redeploy that bazooka
to the right side of the road.

676
01:00:27,534 --> 01:00:30,327
- Yes, sir!
- And get Ryan up here.

677
01:00:32,664 --> 01:00:35,583
LIEUTENANT: Ryan! Ryan,
front and centre!

678
01:00:36,084 --> 01:00:37,376
Ryan!

679
01:00:41,047 --> 01:00:43,048
Here comes our boy.

680
01:00:50,849 --> 01:00:53,559
Told you he was an asshole.

681
01:00:54,895 --> 01:00:57,188
- Sir, Private Ryan reporting as ordered.
- At ease.

682
01:00:57,731 --> 01:01:01,108
Captain Miller, 2nd Rangers.
He wants a word with you.

683
01:01:02,736 --> 01:01:04,236
This way.

684
01:01:05,071 --> 01:01:07,865
All right. Take a knee.

685
01:01:17,417 --> 01:01:20,753
Private, I'm afraid
I have some bad news for you.

686
01:01:28,428 --> 01:01:32,139
Well, there isn't any real
easy way to say this, so...

687
01:01:34,517 --> 01:01:37,770
So I'll just say it.
Your brothers are dead.

688
01:01:39,189 --> 01:01:42,942
We have orders to come get you

689
01:01:43,944 --> 01:01:46,111
because you're going home.

690
01:02:00,043 --> 01:02:02,670
Oh, my God. My brothers are dead.

691
01:02:10,136 --> 01:02:13,764
(CRYING) I was supposed to
take them fishing when we got home.

692
01:02:16,643 --> 01:02:18,310
(RYAN SNIFFLING)

693
01:02:27,487 --> 01:02:30,656
MILLER: I'm so sorry, James.
I can't tell you how much.

694
01:02:31,992 --> 01:02:36,328
- How... How did they die?
- They were killed in action.

695
01:02:38,832 --> 01:02:41,750
That can't be. They're...

696
01:02:42,502 --> 01:02:46,463
That... That can't be.
My brothers are still in grammar school.

697
01:02:49,843 --> 01:02:52,803
- You're James Ryan?
- Yeah.

698
01:02:53,930 --> 01:02:56,682
James Francis Ryan from Iowa?

699
01:02:57,183 --> 01:02:59,727
James Frederick Ryan, Minnesota.

700
01:03:06,651 --> 01:03:08,902
What? Does that mean
my brothers are okay?

701
01:03:08,987 --> 01:03:10,696
Yeah, I'm sure they're fine.

702
01:03:10,780 --> 01:03:12,573
Are you sure they're okay, though?

703
01:03:12,657 --> 01:03:14,074
We're looking
for a different Private Ryan.

704
01:03:14,159 --> 01:03:16,160
This is just a big foul-up.

705
01:03:16,244 --> 01:03:18,120
How do you know?
How can you be sure?

706
01:03:18,204 --> 01:03:22,333
How do you know the foul-up isn't
that his brothers are okay and that...

707
01:03:22,417 --> 01:03:24,585
Lieutenant, I'm sorry for the trouble.

708
01:03:24,669 --> 01:03:28,839
I just wrote them a letter right
before I left. I got to get home.

709
01:03:30,133 --> 01:03:32,092
I got to get home right now.

710
01:03:32,177 --> 01:03:34,678
- I wanna go home.
- SOLDIER: Easy, now.

711
01:03:35,597 --> 01:03:37,139
- So, where in the hell is our Ryan?
- I don't know.

712
01:03:37,223 --> 01:03:39,308
Are you in touch with your CO?

713
01:03:39,392 --> 01:03:41,268
- That figures.
- What unit's your Ryan in?

714
01:03:41,353 --> 01:03:43,562
Baker Company, 506th.

715
01:03:43,646 --> 01:03:45,189
The guy with the broken foot,
he's 506, right?

716
01:03:45,273 --> 01:03:46,940
Yeah. Charlie, I think.

717
01:03:47,025 --> 01:03:48,692
- You think?
- Yeah.

718
01:03:48,777 --> 01:03:52,029
Ryan? Don't know... Man!

719
01:03:52,113 --> 01:03:54,698
- MILLER: Where was your drop zone?
- Just inside of Vierville.

720
01:03:54,783 --> 01:03:57,659
MILLER: Vierville? How the hell did you
end up way up here?

721
01:03:57,744 --> 01:04:00,996
You got me, sir. C-47 took heavy fire.

722
01:04:01,081 --> 01:04:03,832
Pilot went crazy trying to get out
of there, turning every which way.

723
01:04:03,917 --> 01:04:07,878
Took more fire on the drop.
Got messy. I ended up here.

724
01:04:07,962 --> 01:04:10,005
I haven't seen a single guy
from my stick, sir.

725
01:04:10,090 --> 01:04:11,507
God knows where they are.

726
01:04:11,591 --> 01:04:13,300
Anybody from Baker Company
have, like, a big mouth?

727
01:04:13,385 --> 01:04:15,177
Talk about where the drop zone
might've been?

728
01:04:15,261 --> 01:04:18,764
No, sir, but I know Baker Company
had the same rally point as us.

729
01:04:18,848 --> 01:04:20,099
Show me.

730
01:04:21,518 --> 01:04:22,518
My men are beat.

731
01:04:22,602 --> 01:04:24,561
We're gonna hold up here
for about three hours.

732
01:04:24,646 --> 01:04:27,189
We'll pull out after dark.

733
01:04:27,273 --> 01:04:30,192
Got anything left in this town
like a three-star hotel?

734
01:04:30,276 --> 01:04:33,487
Something with clean sheets
and soft pillows and room service?

735
01:04:33,571 --> 01:04:37,032
- How about a nice, comfy church?
- We'll take that.

736
01:04:37,117 --> 01:04:39,952
What have you heard?
How's it all falling together?

737
01:04:40,036 --> 01:04:41,662
Well, we got the beachhead secure.

738
01:04:41,746 --> 01:04:44,373
Problem is Monty's taking
his time moving on Caen.

739
01:04:44,457 --> 01:04:46,708
We can't pull out till he's ready, so...

740
01:04:46,793 --> 01:04:49,420
- That guy's overrated.
- No argument here.

741
01:04:49,504 --> 01:04:52,297
You gotta take Caen,
so you can take Saint-Lô.

742
01:04:52,382 --> 01:04:54,299
You got to take Saint-Lô
to take Valognes.

743
01:04:54,384 --> 01:04:56,051
Valognes, you got Cherbourg.

744
01:04:56,136 --> 01:04:59,471
- Cherbourg, you got Paris.
- Paris, you get Berlin.

745
01:04:59,931 --> 01:05:02,307
And then that big boat home.

746
01:05:05,645 --> 01:05:07,187
We sure as hell
could use you around here,

747
01:05:07,272 --> 01:05:09,481
but I understand what you're doing.

748
01:05:09,566 --> 01:05:11,191
- You do?
- Yeah.

749
01:05:11,317 --> 01:05:13,902
I got a couple of brothers myself.

750
01:05:14,446 --> 01:05:16,989
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

751
01:05:17,323 --> 01:05:21,326
No, I mean it. Find him. Get him home.

752
01:05:29,752 --> 01:05:31,753
HORVATH: What's with your hand?

753
01:05:33,214 --> 01:05:35,048
I don't know.

754
01:05:36,759 --> 01:05:38,093
It started in Portsmouth

755
01:05:38,178 --> 01:05:39,845
when they brought us
down for embarkation.

756
01:05:39,971 --> 01:05:41,430
It comes and goes.

757
01:05:41,514 --> 01:05:44,433
Well, you may have to get
yourself a new line of work.

758
01:05:44,517 --> 01:05:47,895
This one doesn't seem
to agree with you any more.

759
01:05:50,356 --> 01:05:51,899
(LAUGHING)

760
01:05:53,193 --> 01:05:54,526
What?

761
01:05:59,157 --> 01:06:00,741
- What?
- Nothing.

762
01:06:01,534 --> 01:06:04,286
What was the name
of that kid at Anzio?

763
01:06:04,370 --> 01:06:06,872
The one that was always walking
around on his hands, you know?

764
01:06:06,998 --> 01:06:10,584
And he was singing that song
about the man on the flying trapeze.

765
01:06:10,668 --> 01:06:12,377
- Vecchio.
- Vecchio.

766
01:06:12,462 --> 01:06:14,129
(BOTH LAUGHING)

767
01:06:18,968 --> 01:06:20,302
Yeah, Vecchio.

768
01:06:20,386 --> 01:06:22,262
He was a goofy kid.

769
01:06:24,057 --> 01:06:27,017
Remember, he used to pee
a "V" on everybody's jacket

770
01:06:27,101 --> 01:06:30,395
for Vecchio, for victory.

771
01:06:35,026 --> 01:06:38,779
MILLER: He was so short.
He was a midget, wasn't he?

772
01:06:38,863 --> 01:06:41,615
"How did you get to be a Ranger?"

773
01:06:42,867 --> 01:06:44,117
HORVATH: He got shot in the foot once,
didn't he,

774
01:06:44,202 --> 01:06:45,202
when he was walking on his hands?

775
01:06:45,286 --> 01:06:48,247
MILLER: Yeah. He could walk
faster on his hands.

776
01:06:49,374 --> 01:06:52,417
He could run faster on his hands than...

777
01:06:55,338 --> 01:06:56,713
Vecchio.

778
01:06:57,840 --> 01:06:59,091
Yeah.

779
01:07:00,760 --> 01:07:02,094
Caparzo.

780
01:07:08,601 --> 01:07:13,522
You see, when you end up
killing one of your men,

781
01:07:14,399 --> 01:07:17,526
you tell yourself it happened

782
01:07:17,610 --> 01:07:23,240
so you could save the lives
of two or three or 10 others.

783
01:07:24,909 --> 01:07:26,952
Maybe 100 others.

784
01:07:31,165 --> 01:07:34,126
Do you know how many men
I've lost under my command?

785
01:07:34,210 --> 01:07:36,461
- How many?
- Ninety-four.

786
01:07:37,839 --> 01:07:43,635
But that means I've saved the lives
of 10 times that many, doesn't it?

787
01:07:44,596 --> 01:07:48,015
Maybe even 20, right?
Twenty times as many?

788
01:07:54,147 --> 01:07:56,481
And that's how simple it is.

789
01:07:57,400 --> 01:07:59,109
That's how you...

790
01:08:00,445 --> 01:08:03,113
That's how you rationalise
making the choice

791
01:08:03,197 --> 01:08:05,699
between the mission and the men.

792
01:08:06,159 --> 01:08:09,244
Except this time, the mission is a man.

793
01:08:12,540 --> 01:08:15,000
This Ryan better be worth it.

794
01:08:18,004 --> 01:08:20,797
He'd better go home,
cure some disease,

795
01:08:20,882 --> 01:08:24,384
or invent a longer-lasting
light bulb or something.

796
01:08:25,178 --> 01:08:26,887
'Cause the truth is
I wouldn't trade 10 Ryans

797
01:08:26,971 --> 01:08:29,765
for one Vecchio or one Caparzo.

798
01:08:29,849 --> 01:08:31,183
Amen.

799
01:08:33,561 --> 01:08:35,687
Look. There it goes again.

800
01:08:36,731 --> 01:08:39,691
Sir, are you all right?

801
01:08:44,947 --> 01:08:48,241
Now, look, we're gonna
move out in two hours.

802
01:08:48,326 --> 01:08:50,619
Why don't you get some sleep?

803
01:08:50,703 --> 01:08:53,747
REIBEN: I don't know how he does it.
MELLISH: What's that?

804
01:08:53,831 --> 01:08:56,500
Falls asleep like that.
I mean, look at him.

805
01:08:56,584 --> 01:08:59,628
The guy's lights out the minute
his head hits the pack.

806
01:08:59,712 --> 01:09:01,296
Clear conscience.

807
01:09:01,381 --> 01:09:02,964
Yeah. What's that saying?

808
01:09:03,049 --> 01:09:06,218
"If God's on our side,
who the hell could be on theirs?"

809
01:09:06,302 --> 01:09:08,887
"If God be for us,
who could be against us?"

810
01:09:08,971 --> 01:09:11,098
REIBEN: Yeah, what did I say?

811
01:09:11,182 --> 01:09:15,435
WADE: Well, actually, the trick to falling
asleep is trying to stay awake.

812
01:09:15,520 --> 01:09:17,312
How is that, Wade?

813
01:09:17,397 --> 01:09:22,359
Well, when my mother was an intern,
she used to work late through the night,

814
01:09:22,443 --> 01:09:24,986
sleep through the day.

815
01:09:25,071 --> 01:09:26,905
So the only time that we ever got
to talk about anything

816
01:09:26,989 --> 01:09:28,448
was when she'd get home.

817
01:09:28,533 --> 01:09:31,076
So what I used to do,
I used to lie in my bed

818
01:09:31,160 --> 01:09:32,661
and try to stay awake as long as I could,

819
01:09:32,745 --> 01:09:36,498
but it never worked
'cause the harder I tried,

820
01:09:36,582 --> 01:09:38,792
the faster I'd fall asleep.

821
01:09:40,169 --> 01:09:42,170
REIBEN: Yeah. Well, that wouldn't have
mattered none in my house.

822
01:09:42,255 --> 01:09:44,381
My ma, she would've come home,
shook me awake,

823
01:09:44,465 --> 01:09:46,299
chatted me up till dawn.

824
01:09:46,759 --> 01:09:48,927
I swear, that woman
was never too tired to talk.

825
01:09:49,011 --> 01:09:53,014
Yeah. That's probably the only time
she could get a word in.

826
01:09:57,061 --> 01:10:00,605
Funny thing is,
sometimes she'd come home early,

827
01:10:00,690 --> 01:10:03,358
and I'd pretend to be asleep.

828
01:10:03,443 --> 01:10:07,070
- MELLISH: Who? Your mum?
- Yeah.

829
01:10:09,782 --> 01:10:12,784
She'd stand in the doorway,
looking at me.

830
01:10:13,244 --> 01:10:15,662
And I'd just keep my eyes shut.

831
01:10:18,458 --> 01:10:22,043
And I knew she just wanted
to find out about my day,

832
01:10:22,628 --> 01:10:25,088
that she came home early

833
01:10:26,507 --> 01:10:28,467
just to talk to me.

834
01:10:31,679 --> 01:10:35,891
And I still wouldn't move.
I'd still pretend to just be asleep.

835
01:10:43,107 --> 01:10:45,400
I don't know why I did that.

836
01:10:58,956 --> 01:11:02,542
MILLER: We only got a couple of hours.
Shut up and go to sleep.

837
01:11:11,344 --> 01:11:14,179
Captain? Sir?

838
01:11:16,224 --> 01:11:17,682
Corporal?

839
01:11:22,897 --> 01:11:25,982
How you doing there? Are you all right?

840
01:11:26,150 --> 01:11:29,152
Yeah, I think this is all good for me, sir.

841
01:11:30,571 --> 01:11:32,030
Really?

842
01:11:32,782 --> 01:11:34,282
How is that?

843
01:11:38,204 --> 01:11:40,747
"War educates the senses,

844
01:11:40,832 --> 01:11:42,791
"calls into action the will,

845
01:11:42,875 --> 01:11:45,585
"perfects the physical constitution,

846
01:11:45,962 --> 01:11:48,839
"brings men into such swift
and close collision

847
01:11:48,923 --> 01:11:52,050
"in critical moments
that man measures man."

848
01:11:52,510 --> 01:11:55,220
Yeah. Well, I guess
that's Emerson's way

849
01:11:55,680 --> 01:11:57,472
of finding the bright side.

850
01:11:57,557 --> 01:12:01,226
- You know Emerson, sir?
- I know some.

851
01:12:05,690 --> 01:12:09,734
So, where are you from, Captain?
What'd you do before the war?

852
01:12:11,737 --> 01:12:14,072
What's the pool up to?

853
01:12:17,410 --> 01:12:20,245
You know, I think it's around 300, sir.

854
01:12:21,080 --> 01:12:23,748
Well, when it gets up to 500,

855
01:12:23,833 --> 01:12:26,084
I'll give you the answers,
and we'll split the money.

856
01:12:26,168 --> 01:12:28,169
How about that?

857
01:12:28,254 --> 01:12:31,840
Well, if that's the way you feel, sir.
I feel it's my duty under your command

858
01:12:31,924 --> 01:12:36,177
to suggest that we wait
until it gets up to 1,000, sir.

859
01:12:37,889 --> 01:12:40,390
What if we don't live that long?

860
01:12:43,561 --> 01:12:46,646
- 500?
- 500 would be good, yeah.

861
01:12:46,731 --> 01:12:48,690
- Yes, sir.
- Yeah.

862
01:12:51,319 --> 01:12:54,070
- Get some sleep, Corporal.
- Yes, sir.

863
01:13:04,415 --> 01:13:06,416
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

864
01:14:00,680 --> 01:14:02,889
SOLDIER 1: Who's got sulfa powder?

865
01:14:05,267 --> 01:14:09,437
Medic! My buddy's bleeding!
He needs a tourniquet!

866
01:14:09,522 --> 01:14:11,022
- Wade.
- Yes, sir?

867
01:14:11,107 --> 01:14:13,066
- See what you can do.
- Yes, sir.

868
01:14:13,150 --> 01:14:16,486
Hold on, fellas. It won't be much longer.

869
01:14:16,654 --> 01:14:18,530
How we doing here?

870
01:14:19,156 --> 01:14:20,448
All right.

871
01:14:20,533 --> 01:14:23,076
Yeah, doing all right.
Don't worry about it.

872
01:14:23,160 --> 01:14:24,911
Doc's in town.

873
01:14:25,371 --> 01:14:26,454
It's all right. It's all right.

874
01:14:26,539 --> 01:14:28,039
Don't worry, fellas.

875
01:14:28,124 --> 01:14:30,667
The 29th Infantry's breaking through,
they'll be here soon.

876
01:14:30,751 --> 01:14:33,128
SOLDIER 1: Plasma.
Anybody got plasma?

877
01:14:33,212 --> 01:14:37,048
- Captain. Hey, Captain.
- Soldier, you want to fill me in?

878
01:14:37,133 --> 01:14:39,092
Yeah. Lieutenant DeWindt, sir.

879
01:14:39,176 --> 01:14:42,804
99th Troop Carrier Squadron,
carrying in 327th Glider Infantry.

880
01:14:42,888 --> 01:14:44,472
This one was mine, sir.

881
01:14:44,557 --> 01:14:45,974
- I was the pilot.
- Private?

882
01:14:46,058 --> 01:14:47,559
- Twenty-two men dead.
- Private, take care of...

883
01:14:47,643 --> 01:14:50,478
I ended up over there without a scratch.
It took my co-pilot's head right off.

884
01:14:50,563 --> 01:14:52,188
Well, where's the unit?
Who are these people?

885
01:14:52,273 --> 01:14:55,275
Well, the guys we came in with, sir,
they headed off first night.

886
01:14:55,359 --> 01:14:56,651
Haven't seen them since.

887
01:14:56,736 --> 01:15:00,780
Meantime, other guys keep showing up,
one, two, half-dozen at a time.

888
01:15:00,865 --> 01:15:03,658
Then some officer'll come along
and patch together a mixed unit,

889
01:15:03,743 --> 01:15:04,868
head off to make trouble, sir.

890
01:15:04,952 --> 01:15:06,202
SOLDIER 2: Water.
I need a canteen over here.

891
01:15:06,287 --> 01:15:08,288
We're looking for a Private James Ryan.

892
01:15:08,372 --> 01:15:10,623
He's in Baker Company,
the 506 of the 101 st.

893
01:15:10,708 --> 01:15:13,043
No, you got me, sir.
A lot of guys come in and out of here.

894
01:15:13,127 --> 01:15:14,586
- Upham.
- Yes, sir.

895
01:15:14,670 --> 01:15:16,504
Check out that squad.
See if Ryan's in it.

896
01:15:16,589 --> 01:15:18,256
Yes, sir.

897
01:15:19,633 --> 01:15:21,092
Reiben.

898
01:15:21,594 --> 01:15:25,638
Smell that leg right there.
Find out if it's south of cheese.

899
01:15:31,270 --> 01:15:32,604
WADE: What?

900
01:15:34,356 --> 01:15:35,565
Juden.

901
01:15:37,485 --> 01:15:39,444
- Juden.
- SOLDIER: Keep moving.

902
01:15:39,528 --> 01:15:41,404
- Keep moving!
- Juden.

903
01:15:42,323 --> 01:15:44,699
I'm Juden, you know?

904
01:15:46,952 --> 01:15:49,537
Yeah, I couldn't pry him out of there,
hard as I tried.

905
01:15:49,622 --> 01:15:51,831
- I'd need a winch.
- Yeah.

906
01:15:55,961 --> 01:15:57,253
HORVATH: Stars.

907
01:15:57,630 --> 01:16:02,175
Yep, Brigadier General Amend,
Deputy Commander, 101 st.

908
01:16:03,010 --> 01:16:05,553
Some fucking genius had the great idea

909
01:16:05,638 --> 01:16:07,180
of welding a couple of steel plates

910
01:16:07,264 --> 01:16:10,558
onto our deck to keep
the general safe from ground fire.

911
01:16:10,643 --> 01:16:12,227
Unfortunately,
they forgot to tell me about it

912
01:16:12,311 --> 01:16:14,729
until we were just getting airborne.

913
01:16:14,814 --> 01:16:17,816
Well, that's like trying
to fly a freight train. Okay.

914
01:16:18,442 --> 01:16:21,820
Gross overload.
Trim characteristics all shot to hell.

915
01:16:22,196 --> 01:16:25,198
I nearly broke both my arms
trying to keep her level.

916
01:16:25,282 --> 01:16:27,408
(STAMMERING) And when we released,

917
01:16:27,493 --> 01:16:29,786
you know, I cut as hard as I could,

918
01:16:29,870 --> 01:16:33,373
tried to gain some altitude
and still keep her from stalling.

919
01:16:33,457 --> 01:16:37,627
We came down like a fucking meteor.
And this is how we ended up.

920
01:16:39,797 --> 01:16:43,091
And the others, they stopped easy
enough okay though, you know?

921
01:16:43,175 --> 01:16:46,928
We were just... We were just
too damn heavy, you know?

922
01:16:47,012 --> 01:16:48,847
The grass was wet.

923
01:16:49,682 --> 01:16:51,808
Downward slope and all.

924
01:16:52,518 --> 01:16:54,435
Twenty-two guys dead.

925
01:16:57,231 --> 01:17:00,733
- All that for a general?
- One man.

926
01:17:03,028 --> 01:17:06,281
- A lot of that going around.
- FUBAR.

927
01:17:06,866 --> 01:17:08,867
- FUBAR.
- FUBAR.

928
01:17:09,618 --> 01:17:11,035
FUBAR.

929
01:17:11,120 --> 01:17:13,246
You all got that right.

930
01:17:13,747 --> 01:17:15,665
Hey, I looked up "FUBAR"
in the German dictionary.

931
01:17:15,749 --> 01:17:16,791
There's no "FUBAR" in there.

932
01:17:16,876 --> 01:17:18,126
- MILLER: Upham.
- Yes, sir?

933
01:17:18,210 --> 01:17:20,795
There's more paratroops out there.
Find out if one of them is Ryan.

934
01:17:20,880 --> 01:17:22,297
UPHAM: Yes, sir.

935
01:17:22,381 --> 01:17:25,049
Oh, you might want
to check these out, sir.

936
01:17:25,134 --> 01:17:26,676
Dog tags.

937
01:17:26,760 --> 01:17:29,679
More than I really want to count, sir.

938
01:17:30,890 --> 01:17:33,725
I've covered a lot of bodies, sir.

939
01:17:33,893 --> 01:17:35,268
MILLER: Jackson.

940
01:17:35,895 --> 01:17:38,730
- Start going through those.
- Yes, sir.

941
01:17:39,982 --> 01:17:41,566
I'll help.

942
01:17:43,777 --> 01:17:46,321
What do you think, Jackson?
Do you think that little prick's in there?

943
01:17:46,405 --> 01:17:49,407
Well, if he is, I'm gonna find him.
I bet that son of a bitch is here.

944
01:17:49,491 --> 01:17:51,409
I got big money saying
this guy's still alive.

945
01:17:51,493 --> 01:17:53,620
MELLISH: 10 bucks says I nail him first.

946
01:17:53,704 --> 01:17:56,331
- Let's see who we got in here.
- You mugs don't stand a chance.

947
01:17:56,415 --> 01:17:58,291
All right, you think this little
shit bird is in here or what?

948
01:17:58,375 --> 01:18:00,084
Just keep looking.

949
01:18:00,544 --> 01:18:02,712
All right. Gary lanico.

950
01:18:02,796 --> 01:18:04,589
Ben Rubino. Mike Cessacchio.

951
01:18:04,673 --> 01:18:06,466
I swear.
All the guineas are buying it, huh?

952
01:18:06,550 --> 01:18:08,343
MELLISH: Oh, come on,
not the right name.

953
01:18:08,427 --> 01:18:11,429
Wee Willie Winkie,
that's a buddy of yours.

954
01:18:11,680 --> 01:18:14,057
REIBEN: We gotta find this prick.

955
01:18:18,395 --> 01:18:20,230
Where is this son of a bitch?

956
01:18:20,314 --> 01:18:22,857
Don't mix them up, Jackson, all right?
Keep them in your own fucking pile.

957
01:18:22,942 --> 01:18:25,276
How am I supposed to know
who we got?

958
01:18:25,361 --> 01:18:28,029
Why don't you just shut up,
Reiben? All right.

959
01:18:28,113 --> 01:18:31,616
REIBEN: Everybody be friends.
MELLISH: Cranky there, huh?

960
01:18:32,743 --> 01:18:35,536
- I think I got a winner.
- What you talking about?

961
01:18:35,621 --> 01:18:37,080
Ryan.

962
01:18:37,289 --> 01:18:39,874
- Ryan.
- Take a look at that, Mellish.

963
01:18:40,417 --> 01:18:41,709
You know what?
You're a genius. You really are.

964
01:18:41,794 --> 01:18:43,628
R- I-E-N-N-E.

965
01:18:43,712 --> 01:18:45,672
That's Rienne and that's French.
All right.

966
01:18:45,756 --> 01:18:47,840
- You know what that means?
- JACKSON: It means nothing.

967
01:18:47,925 --> 01:18:49,884
MELLISH: What beats three of a kind?
JACKSON: I got shit here.

968
01:18:49,969 --> 01:18:53,680
- I got all guys from New York.
- MELLISH: I got a full house.

969
01:18:53,764 --> 01:18:55,890
REIBEN: Do you need a hand with that?
MELLISH: I got a full house.

970
01:18:55,975 --> 01:18:58,559
- I got you beat. I got the straight flush.
- Full house, he's got.

971
01:18:58,644 --> 01:19:02,021
You were looking at my tags.
You're cheating, you know?

972
01:19:02,106 --> 01:19:04,232
- Ryan.
- Fucking unreal, this guy.

973
01:19:04,316 --> 01:19:06,901
REIBEN: Do you need a hand with that?
Can you read that shit?

974
01:19:06,986 --> 01:19:09,570
Jesus Christ. Look at this poor bastard.

975
01:19:09,655 --> 01:19:11,364
MELLISH: I guess they're
not bullet-proof, huh?

976
01:19:11,448 --> 01:19:12,740
REIBEN: Guess not. All right?

977
01:19:12,825 --> 01:19:14,242
I don't like
what he's got between his ears.

978
01:19:14,326 --> 01:19:17,245
JACKSON: Sort of like what you fellas
got between your legs.

979
01:19:17,329 --> 01:19:19,414
MELLISH: We got to give him that.
REIBEN: That's not bad.

980
01:19:19,498 --> 01:19:20,999
Not bad with you, Jackson.

981
01:19:21,083 --> 01:19:23,084
All right, I got three of a kind.
All right.

982
01:19:23,168 --> 01:19:24,335
- Full house.
- What the hell are you doing?

983
01:19:24,420 --> 01:19:26,921
The whole goddamn
Airborne's watching.

984
01:19:27,006 --> 01:19:28,464
These aren't poker chips.

985
01:19:28,549 --> 01:19:32,385
- JACKSON: All right, all right, all right.
- Put them back in there!

986
01:19:55,909 --> 01:19:57,577
He's not here.

987
01:20:02,041 --> 01:20:04,417
Maybe we should bust up
into a couple of different groups, huh?

988
01:20:04,543 --> 01:20:05,752
And wander the woods
like Hansel and Gretel,

989
01:20:05,878 --> 01:20:06,919
calling his name.

990
01:20:07,046 --> 01:20:10,173
He's bound to hear us sooner
or later. Ryan!

991
01:20:10,257 --> 01:20:13,426
That might be
a little hard to do, Captain.

992
01:20:14,136 --> 01:20:16,304
Maybe the locals have seen him.
Hey, you know...

993
01:20:16,388 --> 01:20:17,638
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

994
01:20:17,723 --> 01:20:20,516
Ryan? James Ryan?
Merci. Merci beaucoup.

995
01:20:20,726 --> 01:20:23,227
Ryan! Anybody know Ryan,
101 st Airborne?

996
01:20:23,312 --> 01:20:27,106
Ryan? You know a guy named Ryan?
Private James Ryan from Iowa?

997
01:20:27,232 --> 01:20:29,233
Anybody know a Ryan?

998
01:20:29,735 --> 01:20:31,652
James Ryan!

999
01:20:31,737 --> 01:20:37,700
Hey, Joe, doesn't Mandelsohn pal
around with a Ryan from C Company?

1000
01:20:37,785 --> 01:20:41,079
- Yeah. I think so.
- Bring him up here, would you?

1001
01:20:50,422 --> 01:20:52,965
- Do you know Private Ryan?
- You're gonna have to speak up, sir.

1002
01:20:53,092 --> 01:20:54,258
(YELLING) You're gonna have to
speak up, sir.

1003
01:20:54,343 --> 01:20:56,010
- My hearing is not good!
- It comes and goes!

1004
01:20:56,095 --> 01:20:57,303
- It comes and goes!
- A German grenade went off

1005
01:20:57,429 --> 01:20:59,222
- next to his ear.
- A grenade went off right by my head!

1006
01:20:59,306 --> 01:21:02,350
Got it, got it. Do you know Private Ryan?

1007
01:21:02,434 --> 01:21:03,893
Who?

1008
01:21:03,977 --> 01:21:06,437
Private Ryan! James Ryan!

1009
01:21:06,522 --> 01:21:10,733
- Jimmy Ryan?
- James! James Francis Ryan!

1010
01:21:10,818 --> 01:21:14,654
- No, no, no. James Francis Ryan.
- All right. Get me a pencil.

1011
01:21:14,780 --> 01:21:17,073
Something to write on.
Something to write on.

1012
01:21:17,157 --> 01:21:19,659
Quick! Quick! Come on, a pencil!

1013
01:21:21,453 --> 01:21:23,204
A small one, sir.

1014
01:21:23,831 --> 01:21:24,956
Write this down.

1015
01:21:25,040 --> 01:21:26,999
James Francis Ryan, question mark.

1016
01:21:27,126 --> 01:21:28,876
Iowa, question mark.

1017
01:21:28,961 --> 01:21:31,462
Do you know him? Does he know him?

1018
01:21:31,547 --> 01:21:33,631
Read the message. Look.

1019
01:21:35,467 --> 01:21:39,470
- Yeah. Of course I know him, sir.
- Does he know where he is?

1020
01:21:43,308 --> 01:21:46,686
Yeah, yeah. We missed
our drop zone by about 20 miles,

1021
01:21:46,812 --> 01:21:50,106
ended up way over
by Bumville or some damn place.

1022
01:21:50,190 --> 01:21:53,317
Him, me and a couple of other guys
were coming here to the rally point,

1023
01:21:53,402 --> 01:21:58,573
ran into a Colonel who was gathering
up men to go to Ramelle.

1024
01:21:58,907 --> 01:21:59,991
Ramelle.

1025
01:22:00,075 --> 01:22:02,535
To baby-sit a bridge.
That's the last I've seen of him, sir.

1026
01:22:02,661 --> 01:22:04,537
Great! Great! Thank you.

1027
01:22:04,663 --> 01:22:06,914
Write thank... Read, and thank you.

1028
01:22:06,999 --> 01:22:09,500
- MANDELSOHN: You're welcome!
- Assemble on me.

1029
01:22:11,670 --> 01:22:13,671
Thank you, Lieutenant.

1030
01:22:16,258 --> 01:22:17,675
Ramelle.

1031
01:22:19,219 --> 01:22:21,387
We're here. There.

1032
01:22:21,847 --> 01:22:27,101
Ramelle is on the Merderet River,
right here, just to the southwest of us.

1033
01:22:27,186 --> 01:22:29,562
You know anything about this bridge
he was talking about, Captain?

1034
01:22:29,688 --> 01:22:33,524
Yep. The target has
always been Cherbourg.

1035
01:22:34,276 --> 01:22:37,778
We can't push on Paris
until we take a deep water port.

1036
01:22:37,863 --> 01:22:39,655
And Rommel knows that,

1037
01:22:39,740 --> 01:22:41,324
so he's gonna try to get his armour

1038
01:22:41,408 --> 01:22:44,785
across the Merderet river
anywhere he can.

1039
01:22:44,870 --> 01:22:46,871
That way, he can hit
our invasion forces in the flank

1040
01:22:46,955 --> 01:22:49,624
when we make
the big right turn to Cherbourg.

1041
01:22:49,708 --> 01:22:51,417
That makes any village on that river

1042
01:22:51,543 --> 01:22:54,795
with an intact bridge
solid gold real estate.

1043
01:23:15,484 --> 01:23:16,901
Let's go.

1044
01:23:26,411 --> 01:23:27,745
MELLISH: Captain.

1045
01:24:06,118 --> 01:24:08,077
HORVATH: What the hell is that?

1046
01:24:09,288 --> 01:24:12,415
MILLER: A radar site.
It's gotta be out of action.

1047
01:24:12,499 --> 01:24:17,295
Looks like we got something in that.
Sandbag bunker right under the station.

1048
01:24:18,463 --> 01:24:21,340
- See it?
- Yeah. That's my guess, too.

1049
01:24:22,759 --> 01:24:24,510
What is it?

1050
01:24:25,178 --> 01:24:27,471
Machine gun. Probably MG42.

1051
01:24:27,556 --> 01:24:29,849
Jesus. Is that what got those guys?

1052
01:24:29,933 --> 01:24:31,851
Maybe one of them's our boy.

1053
01:24:31,977 --> 01:24:35,354
MILLER: No, their patches are 82nd,
so your luck's not that good.

1054
01:24:35,439 --> 01:24:37,523
Yeah, well, I don't know how fast
the rest of you betties are,

1055
01:24:37,608 --> 01:24:40,109
but I'm thinking we detour
this way quick and quiet,

1056
01:24:40,193 --> 01:24:43,237
the krauts will never
even know we were here.

1057
01:24:43,322 --> 01:24:46,907
So, Captain, what I'm trying to say is
why don't we just go around the thing?

1058
01:24:46,992 --> 01:24:50,411
I hear what you're saying,
but we can't go around it.

1059
01:24:52,039 --> 01:24:53,914
I'm with Reiben on this one, sir.

1060
01:24:53,999 --> 01:24:58,127
- I mean, we left them 88s.
- For the Air Force.

1061
01:24:58,211 --> 01:25:02,298
The Air Force isn't gonna spend
ordnance on one machine gun.

1062
01:25:02,758 --> 01:25:04,216
Captain...

1063
01:25:05,260 --> 01:25:07,094
We can still skip it
and accomplish our mission.

1064
01:25:07,179 --> 01:25:10,181
I mean, this isn't our mission, right, sir?

1065
01:25:10,265 --> 01:25:12,475
Oh. That's what
you want to do, Mellish?

1066
01:25:12,559 --> 01:25:14,018
You just want to leave it here,
so they can ambush

1067
01:25:14,102 --> 01:25:15,394
the next company that comes along?

1068
01:25:15,479 --> 01:25:16,854
No, sir. That's not what I'm saying.

1069
01:25:16,938 --> 01:25:19,732
I'm simply saying
it seems like an unnecessary risk,

1070
01:25:19,816 --> 01:25:21,275
given our objective, sir.

1071
01:25:21,360 --> 01:25:24,111
Our objective is to win the war.

1072
01:25:27,324 --> 01:25:31,327
Sir, I just... I don't have
a good feeling about this one.

1073
01:25:33,830 --> 01:25:37,541
When was the last time
you felt good about anything?

1074
01:25:58,438 --> 01:26:01,607
All right, three runners
with suppressing fire.

1075
01:26:01,733 --> 01:26:04,902
Mellish, you hook to the right.
I'll go up the middle.

1076
01:26:05,070 --> 01:26:06,737
Who's going left?

1077
01:26:13,161 --> 01:26:14,995
Who's going left?

1078
01:26:19,418 --> 01:26:20,835
I'll do it.

1079
01:26:21,795 --> 01:26:24,380
- I'll go left.
- All right.

1080
01:26:24,464 --> 01:26:27,258
Upham, switch off with Jackson,
and you linger in the rear.

1081
01:26:27,342 --> 01:26:28,801
Yes, sir.

1082
01:26:29,511 --> 01:26:34,348
We advance and keep pressure on him
till he has to change out his barrels.

1083
01:26:35,183 --> 01:26:37,143
I think we should be able
to hit him from grenade range.

1084
01:26:37,227 --> 01:26:41,522
- Maybe I should go up the middle, sir.
- The way you run? I don't think so.

1085
01:26:41,606 --> 01:26:45,359
- Maybe I should go left, sir.
- Maybe you should shut up.

1086
01:26:46,153 --> 01:26:48,529
Reiben, base of fire.

1087
01:26:56,913 --> 01:26:59,832
Mags and clips where
you can reach them, and...

1088
01:26:59,916 --> 01:27:02,877
And extra grenades
for the base runners.

1089
01:27:05,547 --> 01:27:07,465
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

1090
01:27:18,643 --> 01:27:19,977
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1091
01:28:27,546 --> 01:28:29,463
HORVATH: Hill's clear!
Four down and dead!

1092
01:28:29,548 --> 01:28:32,758
MILLER: Upham, grab the gear.
Get up here!

1093
01:28:32,843 --> 01:28:34,552
We need water and extra dressing now!

1094
01:28:34,636 --> 01:28:36,887
HORVATH: Get the morphine out
of the extra medical kit!

1095
01:28:36,972 --> 01:28:40,349
MILLER: Get the morphine out
of the extra medical kit!

1096
01:28:49,150 --> 01:28:50,192
God.

1097
01:28:50,861 --> 01:28:52,069
HORVATH: Son of a bitch!

1098
01:28:52,153 --> 01:28:53,404
MILLER: All right. The sulfa.

1099
01:28:53,530 --> 01:28:55,155
- WADE: Put my legs up. Put my legs up.
- I got him.

1100
01:28:55,240 --> 01:28:56,824
- More sulfa, Mellish.
- HORVATH: I got him. I got him, Wade.

1101
01:28:56,908 --> 01:28:58,325
- You're gonna be all right.
- Listen to my voice.

1102
01:28:58,410 --> 01:28:59,660
You're gonna be all right, Doc.

1103
01:28:59,744 --> 01:29:01,328
WADE: How's it look? How's it look?

1104
01:29:01,413 --> 01:29:03,330
Wade, you're fine.
You're going on a hospital ship.

1105
01:29:03,415 --> 01:29:05,332
- More sulfa! More sulfa!
- WADE: Put my legs up.

1106
01:29:05,417 --> 01:29:07,668
- Put my legs up. Put my legs up.
- He's gonna be all right.

1107
01:29:07,752 --> 01:29:10,170
- I got 'em. I got 'em. I got 'em.
- You're gonna be okay, Wade.

1108
01:29:10,255 --> 01:29:11,589
I got 'em.

1109
01:29:11,715 --> 01:29:14,425
Upham, give me your canteen!

1110
01:29:14,551 --> 01:29:16,343
- Come on. Come on.
- ... we're gonna get you out of here.

1111
01:29:16,428 --> 01:29:17,511
MELLISH: Put some pressure on it.

1112
01:29:17,596 --> 01:29:20,472
MILLER: You're gonna be okay.
WADE: How's it look?

1113
01:29:20,599 --> 01:29:22,349
- I'm getting some morphine.
- How's it look?

1114
01:29:22,434 --> 01:29:24,894
- It's all right. You're gonna be okay.
- How's it look?

1115
01:29:24,978 --> 01:29:26,687
You're gonna be okay.

1116
01:29:26,771 --> 01:29:28,647
Here comes the morphine.
Here comes the morphine.

1117
01:29:28,773 --> 01:29:31,775
Am I shot in the spine?

1118
01:29:31,902 --> 01:29:34,445
- You're okay, Wade.
- Am I shot in the spine?

1119
01:29:34,571 --> 01:29:36,614
- Lift him up. Easy, easy, easy.
- All right. Flip him over.

1120
01:29:36,740 --> 01:29:37,907
- Easy, easy, easy.
- Put some pressure.

1121
01:29:37,991 --> 01:29:40,576
- Easy, easy.
- Lift him up. Lift him up.

1122
01:29:43,121 --> 01:29:46,123
It's okay, doc. It's all right.

1123
01:29:46,249 --> 01:29:48,751
Wade, you got an exit wound.

1124
01:29:48,835 --> 01:29:50,586
It's in the small of your back.

1125
01:29:50,670 --> 01:29:53,005
How big's the hole in the...

1126
01:29:53,131 --> 01:29:55,049
- MILLER: About the size of an acorn.
- It's fine.

1127
01:29:55,133 --> 01:29:57,176
You're fine. You're fine.

1128
01:29:58,803 --> 01:30:02,681
HORVATH: Put some pressure on it.
Put some pressure on it.

1129
01:30:02,807 --> 01:30:06,977
- Put some pressure on it.
- It's all right.

1130
01:30:07,103 --> 01:30:09,813
HORVATH:
Put some more pressure on it!

1131
01:30:10,315 --> 01:30:12,691
Is there anything bleeding
worse than the others?

1132
01:30:12,817 --> 01:30:14,568
Yeah, right here, right here.
Do you know what it is?

1133
01:30:14,653 --> 01:30:16,070
- No.
- Right here. Yeah. Right here.

1134
01:30:16,154 --> 01:30:17,780
I'm gonna put your hand on it.

1135
01:30:17,864 --> 01:30:19,657
- We got some pressure on there.
- Right there.

1136
01:30:19,783 --> 01:30:21,909
- That's good.
- Okay. That's the one.

1137
01:30:21,993 --> 01:30:23,786
Oh, my God, my liver!

1138
01:30:23,870 --> 01:30:26,789
- Oh, my God! It's my liver!
- Something wrong, Wade.

1139
01:30:26,873 --> 01:30:28,248
Tell us what to do.
Tell us how to fix you.

1140
01:30:28,333 --> 01:30:30,209
What do you need? What do you need?
What can we do, Wade?

1141
01:30:30,335 --> 01:30:32,544
Tell us what to do.

1142
01:30:32,671 --> 01:30:33,921
Oh, shit.

1143
01:30:34,005 --> 01:30:38,509
I could use... I could use
a little more morphine.

1144
01:30:39,219 --> 01:30:41,011
More morphine, sir?

1145
01:30:42,013 --> 01:30:44,473
Okay. Okay.

1146
01:30:48,144 --> 01:30:49,812
Give it to him.

1147
01:30:52,065 --> 01:30:53,691
Give it to him.

1148
01:30:58,029 --> 01:31:00,739
- (MUMBLES) I don't wanna die.
- Here you go. Wade, here you go.

1149
01:31:00,865 --> 01:31:04,284
- Here it comes.
- There you go. There you...

1150
01:31:07,580 --> 01:31:09,540
Give him another one.

1151
01:31:16,631 --> 01:31:18,048
(WHISPERS) Mama?

1152
01:31:20,427 --> 01:31:21,885
Mama?

1153
01:31:22,721 --> 01:31:25,639
I want to go home. I want to go home.

1154
01:31:27,267 --> 01:31:30,269
Mama. Mama.

1155
01:31:30,395 --> 01:31:33,230
Mama, Mama, Mama...

1156
01:32:10,060 --> 01:32:11,143
(GRUNTING)

1157
01:32:16,024 --> 01:32:17,775
MELLISH: Reiben, hold him!

1158
01:32:31,915 --> 01:32:33,707
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1159
01:32:38,505 --> 01:32:39,880
Not yet.

1160
01:32:42,467 --> 01:32:46,470
First, make him mark and cover
Wade's body for grave detail.

1161
01:32:46,971 --> 01:32:49,973
Same thing
for those paratroopers down there.

1162
01:32:50,391 --> 01:32:52,851
Strip that stuff off
and check him for intelligence.

1163
01:32:52,936 --> 01:32:57,147
Ask this piece of shit
if he's the one who shot Wade. Ask him!

1164
01:32:57,232 --> 01:32:59,066
- It doesn't matter.
- It does matter!

1165
01:32:59,150 --> 01:33:01,151
(BOTH SPEAKING GERMAN)

1166
01:33:02,362 --> 01:33:04,947
Shut up with that filthy pig latin.

1167
01:33:07,033 --> 01:33:08,951
Jackson, you're hit.

1168
01:33:11,121 --> 01:33:12,371
Shit.

1169
01:33:12,956 --> 01:33:16,291
- I guess it just skinned the arm, sir.
- Get it cleaned and dressed.

1170
01:33:16,376 --> 01:33:18,794
You and Sarge, watch the perimeter.

1171
01:33:18,878 --> 01:33:20,671
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1172
01:33:21,965 --> 01:33:26,510
- Sir, he says, "Please don't shoot."
- I don't care what he says, Upham.

1173
01:33:27,262 --> 01:33:30,305
Sir? Sir, you're gonna let them kill him?

1174
01:33:31,307 --> 01:33:35,561
- This is not right, sir.
- You can help him with the bodies.

1175
01:33:37,897 --> 01:33:39,731
What is happening?

1176
01:35:30,218 --> 01:35:31,593
American.

1177
01:35:33,513 --> 01:35:35,264
I like American.

1178
01:35:42,814 --> 01:35:44,147
Steamboat Willie.

1179
01:35:44,232 --> 01:35:45,315
(IMITATES HORN)

1180
01:35:45,400 --> 01:35:46,733
Steamboat Willie.

1181
01:35:46,818 --> 01:35:49,486
Yeah, Steamboat Willie. American.

1182
01:35:54,993 --> 01:35:56,827
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1183
01:36:00,999 --> 01:36:03,375
- He's says he's not finished.
- Yeah. That's what you think.

1184
01:36:03,459 --> 01:36:05,210
Come on. Yeah.

1185
01:36:15,138 --> 01:36:18,515
Please... I like America.

1186
01:36:19,851 --> 01:36:22,060
Fancy schmancy! What a cinch!

1187
01:36:22,145 --> 01:36:25,814
Go fly a kite!
Cat got your tongue? Cool beans!

1188
01:36:29,527 --> 01:36:31,695
Betty Boop! What a dish!

1189
01:36:32,697 --> 01:36:35,490
Betty Grable. Nice gams.

1190
01:36:37,827 --> 01:36:39,828
(PANTING)

1191
01:36:42,165 --> 01:36:47,377
(SINGING) I say can you see
I say can you see

