The Captain just gave you an order.

1222
01:38:52,420 --> 01:38:56,256
Yeah. Like the one he gave
to take this machine gun.

1223
01:38:56,340 --> 01:38:59,468
- That was a real doozy, wasn't it, Sarge.
- Soldier, you are way out of line.

1224
01:38:59,552 --> 01:39:02,804
Yes, sir. That was one hell of a call,
coming to take this nest,

1225
01:39:02,889 --> 01:39:05,640
but what the hell? We only lost
one of our guys, going for it.

1226
01:39:05,725 --> 01:39:08,059
I swear, I hope Mama Ryan's
real fucking happy,

1227
01:39:08,186 --> 01:39:11,730
knowing that little Jimmy's life is a little
bit more important than two of our guys!

1228
01:39:11,856 --> 01:39:14,816
But then again, we haven't
found him yet, have we? Huh?

1229
01:39:16,861 --> 01:39:18,236
- HORVATH: Here you go.
- Get the hell off me!

1230
01:39:18,362 --> 01:39:20,071
HORVATH: Reiben, get up.

1231
01:39:21,866 --> 01:39:24,993
Gear up. Fall in.

1232
01:39:30,041 --> 01:39:32,250
I'm done with this mission.

1233
01:39:37,215 --> 01:39:38,882
Hey! Hey!

1234
01:39:40,843 --> 01:39:42,886
- UPHAM: Sir.
- Don't walk away from your Captain.

1235
01:39:43,012 --> 01:39:45,263
- Reiben, get back in line.
- No, sir.

1236
01:39:45,389 --> 01:39:46,723
I'll spend the rest
of my life in the stockade

1237
01:39:46,849 --> 01:39:48,141
if I have to, but I'm done with this.

1238
01:39:48,226 --> 01:39:50,519
- I'm not gonna ask you again, soldier.
- Captain!

1239
01:39:50,603 --> 01:39:51,937
All right, now. This is bullshit!

1240
01:39:52,063 --> 01:39:54,523
- Fall in!
- You're gonna shoot me over Ryan?

1241
01:39:54,607 --> 01:39:55,982
No. I'm gonna shoot you
'cause I don't like you.

1242
01:39:56,067 --> 01:39:59,027
- UPHAM: Sir, listen...
- Sir, if he wants to go, just let him go!

1243
01:39:59,111 --> 01:40:02,447
Are you letting this happen?
Captain! You see this?

1244
01:40:02,573 --> 01:40:05,617
- Captain? Sir? Sir, Ryan's dead.
- Bullshit!

1245
01:40:05,743 --> 01:40:08,161
- Sir, we have a situation you might...
- That is bullshit!

1246
01:40:08,246 --> 01:40:10,747
Captain, I have a sixth sense about
these things. I know it in my bones.

1247
01:40:10,873 --> 01:40:13,750
We don't kill that son-of-a-bitch kraut.
Now you're gonna shoot me?

1248
01:40:13,876 --> 01:40:16,294
- He's better than you.
- Then why don't you just do it, Sarge?

1249
01:40:16,420 --> 01:40:18,088
Do it, man. Put one in my leg
and give me that...

1250
01:40:18,172 --> 01:40:20,840
I'm gonna shoot you
in your big goddamn mouth!

1251
01:40:20,925 --> 01:40:22,342
Well, put your money
where your mouth is...

1252
01:40:22,426 --> 01:40:23,843
- You don't know when to shut up.
- Do it!

1253
01:40:23,928 --> 01:40:25,512
- You don't know how to shut up.
- Pull the trigger, already!

1254
01:40:25,596 --> 01:40:26,930
Captain, please!

1255
01:40:27,056 --> 01:40:30,267
- What's the pool on me up to?
- What?

1256
01:40:30,393 --> 01:40:33,103
- You are a coward son of a bitch!
- I'm waiting, Sarge.

1257
01:40:33,187 --> 01:40:36,856
Mike, what's the pool
on me up to right now?

1258
01:40:36,941 --> 01:40:38,733
What's it up to?

1259
01:40:39,360 --> 01:40:43,947
What is it, $300? Is that it? 300?
I'm a schoolteacher.

1260
01:40:48,536 --> 01:40:50,787
I teach English composition

1261
01:40:52,123 --> 01:40:54,291
in this little town called
Addley, Pennsylvania.

1262
01:40:54,375 --> 01:40:56,126
The last 11 years,

1263
01:40:56,961 --> 01:40:59,963
I've been at
Thomas Alva Edison High School.

1264
01:41:01,882 --> 01:41:05,552
I was the coach of the baseball team
in the springtime.

1265
01:41:08,097 --> 01:41:09,764
I'll be doggone.

1266
01:41:10,474 --> 01:41:13,727
MILLER: Back home, when I'd tell people
what I do for a living,

1267
01:41:13,811 --> 01:41:16,730
they'd think, "Well, that figures."

1268
01:41:18,608 --> 01:41:20,817
But over here, it's a...

1269
01:41:22,445 --> 01:41:24,112
A big...

1270
01:41:25,364 --> 01:41:27,032
A big mystery.

1271
01:41:28,075 --> 01:41:30,785
So I guess I've changed some.

1272
01:41:33,497 --> 01:41:36,666
Sometimes I wonder
if I've changed so much

1273
01:41:36,751 --> 01:41:41,296
my wife is even going to recognise me
whenever it is I get back to her.

1274
01:41:42,840 --> 01:41:45,383
And how I'll ever be able to...

1275
01:41:47,928 --> 01:41:50,555
To tell her about days like today.

1276
01:41:53,184 --> 01:41:54,559
Ah! Ryan...

1277
01:41:56,270 --> 01:41:59,439
I don't know anything about Ryan.
I don't care.

1278
01:42:00,107 --> 01:42:03,777
The man means nothing to me,
it's just a name. But if...

1279
01:42:05,613 --> 01:42:08,114
You know, if going to Ramelle

1280
01:42:08,240 --> 01:42:09,783
and finding him, so he can go home,

1281
01:42:09,867 --> 01:42:11,493
if that earns me the right
to get back to my wife

1282
01:42:11,577 --> 01:42:15,872
well, then... Then that's my mission.

1283
01:42:17,917 --> 01:42:19,501
You want to leave?

1284
01:42:19,585 --> 01:42:22,629
You want to go off and fight the war?

1285
01:42:25,508 --> 01:42:26,966
All right.

1286
01:42:28,302 --> 01:42:30,845
All right, I won't stop you.

1287
01:42:30,930 --> 01:42:33,515
I'll even put in the paperwork.

1288
01:42:35,476 --> 01:42:39,854
I just know that every man I kill,
the farther away from home I feel.

1289
01:44:05,065 --> 01:44:06,649
(SINGING SOFTLY) By memories

1290
01:44:07,985 --> 01:44:10,028
Of the days gone by

1291
01:44:11,864 --> 01:44:13,656
In my solitude

1292
01:44:14,575 --> 01:44:17,035
You taunt me

1293
01:44:17,119 --> 01:44:20,663
With memories that never die

1294
01:44:21,874 --> 01:44:24,334
I sit in my chair

1295
01:44:24,418 --> 01:44:26,628
Filled with despair

1296
01:44:26,712 --> 01:44:28,546
There's no one

1297
01:44:28,631 --> 01:44:31,049
Could be so sad

1298
01:44:31,926 --> 01:44:33,968
With gloom everywhere

1299
01:44:34,053 --> 01:44:36,679
I sit and I stare...

1300
01:44:50,569 --> 01:44:52,654
Halftrack! Cover!

1301
01:44:54,073 --> 01:44:55,782
(ENGINE RUMBLING)

1302
01:45:08,337 --> 01:45:11,881
Who's doing the shooting?
Who's doing the shooting?

1303
01:45:32,778 --> 01:45:35,154
Get ready to move on their left flank!
Take their left flank!

1304
01:45:35,239 --> 01:45:38,116
MELLISH: Hold on
and make sure they're down!

1305
01:45:59,263 --> 01:46:01,890
SOLDIER: 101 st! We're coming out!

1306
01:46:09,315 --> 01:46:12,275
That was a recon element, 2nd SS.

1307
01:46:13,611 --> 01:46:17,196
We've been expecting a probe.
That must have been it.

1308
01:46:19,074 --> 01:46:22,493
Captain Miller,
Charlie Company, 2nd Rangers.

1309
01:46:22,578 --> 01:46:24,662
Corporal Henderson,
Easy Company, 501 st.

1310
01:46:24,747 --> 01:46:26,247
Ryan. First of the 506th.

1311
01:46:26,332 --> 01:46:28,708
PFC Toynbe, Third of the 506th.

1312
01:46:28,792 --> 01:46:30,752
James Francis Ryan?

1313
01:46:30,836 --> 01:46:33,338
Yes, sir. How'd you guess that?

1314
01:46:45,100 --> 01:46:48,061
MILLER: Looks like you guys
got hit pretty hard.

1315
01:46:48,145 --> 01:46:51,689
HENDERSON: Yes, sir.
Small unit action.

1316
01:46:54,109 --> 01:46:57,695
They came in,
and beat the hell out of us with 88s.

1317
01:47:03,911 --> 01:47:07,455
Tell you what, sir, if you're our relief,
I'm gonna file a complaint.

1318
01:47:07,539 --> 01:47:09,499
I wouldn't blame you.

1319
01:47:10,250 --> 01:47:12,001
Who's your CO?

1320
01:47:13,587 --> 01:47:16,381
HENDERSON: It would have been
Captain Jennings, sir.

1321
01:47:16,465 --> 01:47:20,927
I'm afraid the best we can muster up
right now is a corporal.

1322
01:47:21,011 --> 01:47:23,554
So, what are you guys all about?

1323
01:47:24,139 --> 01:47:26,641
We're here for him. Ryan.

1324
01:47:27,977 --> 01:47:29,435
Me, sir?

1325
01:47:38,779 --> 01:47:41,155
James Francis Ryan of Iowa?

1326
01:47:41,991 --> 01:47:45,451
Yes, sir.
Payton, Iowa, that's correct, but...

1327
01:47:45,536 --> 01:47:47,537
What is this about?

1328
01:47:49,373 --> 01:47:52,166
Your brothers were killed in combat.

1329
01:47:58,966 --> 01:48:00,591
Which ones?

1330
01:48:03,512 --> 01:48:05,013
All of them.

1331
01:48:14,898 --> 01:48:16,482
On the level?

1332
01:48:17,901 --> 01:48:19,861
Yeah. I'm afraid so.

1333
01:48:22,614 --> 01:48:24,574
You might want to take
some time with this.

1334
01:48:24,658 --> 01:48:27,702
If there's someplace
you want to go and...

1335
01:48:36,712 --> 01:48:39,630
- What's this all about?
- Ryan lost his brothers.

1336
01:48:39,715 --> 01:48:42,091
- Which one?
- All of them.

1337
01:48:47,056 --> 01:48:48,431
You...

1338
01:48:51,060 --> 01:48:54,353
You came all the way
out here to tell me that?

1339
01:48:56,065 --> 01:48:58,232
Well, you're going home.

1340
01:48:59,735 --> 01:49:02,320
Our orders are to bring you back.

1341
01:49:05,616 --> 01:49:07,241
Bring me back?

1342
01:49:09,620 --> 01:49:13,122
Corporal Henderson, I don't mean
to leave you even more shorthanded,

1343
01:49:13,207 --> 01:49:14,540
but orders are orders.

1344
01:49:14,625 --> 01:49:17,460
Any communication about when
you're going to be relieved up here?

1345
01:49:17,586 --> 01:49:18,795
Sir, there's no way to tell. I mean,

1346
01:49:18,921 --> 01:49:20,463
we have no idea
what's happening south of us.

1347
01:49:20,547 --> 01:49:21,881
I have my orders, too, sir.

1348
01:49:21,965 --> 01:49:23,883
They don't include me
abandoning my post.

1349
01:49:23,967 --> 01:49:26,886
I understand that,
but this changes things.

1350
01:49:26,970 --> 01:49:29,305
I don't see that it does, sir.

1351
01:49:30,933 --> 01:49:33,976
The Chief of Staff
for the United States Army says it does.

1352
01:49:34,061 --> 01:49:36,896
Sir, our orders are to hold
this bridge at all cost.

1353
01:49:36,980 --> 01:49:39,482
Now, our planes in the 82nd
have taken out every bridge

1354
01:49:39,608 --> 01:49:41,567
across the Merderet
with the exception of two.

1355
01:49:41,652 --> 01:49:43,236
One at Valognes and this one here.

1356
01:49:43,320 --> 01:49:44,570
We let the Germans take them,

1357
01:49:44,655 --> 01:49:46,239
we're gonna lose our foothold
and have to displace.

1358
01:49:46,323 --> 01:49:49,826
MILLER: Private, your outfit
wants to stay, that's one thing.

1359
01:49:49,910 --> 01:49:50,993
But your party's over here.

1360
01:49:51,078 --> 01:49:53,246
Sir, I can't leave
until at least reinforcements...

1361
01:49:53,330 --> 01:49:55,748
You got three minutes
to gather your gear.

1362
01:49:55,833 --> 01:49:57,917
Sir, what about them?
I mean, there's barely hardly enough...

1363
01:49:58,001 --> 01:49:59,502
REIBEN: Hey, asshole!

1364
01:50:00,254 --> 01:50:04,132
Two of our guys already died
trying to find you, all right?

1365
01:50:09,179 --> 01:50:11,848
- Sir?
- That's right.

1366
01:50:21,733 --> 01:50:26,237
- What were their names?
- Irwin Wade and Adrian Caparzo.

1367
01:50:28,198 --> 01:50:29,740
Wade and...

1368
01:50:31,243 --> 01:50:32,702
Caparzo.

1369
01:50:45,090 --> 01:50:47,508
(WHISPERS) It doesn't make any sense.

1370
01:50:49,595 --> 01:50:53,848
It doesn't make sense, sir.
Why? Why do I deserve to go?

1371
01:50:53,932 --> 01:50:58,102
Why not any of these guys?
They all fought just as hard as me!

1372
01:51:01,732 --> 01:51:04,817
Is that what they're
supposed to tell your mother

1373
01:51:04,902 --> 01:51:08,237
when they send her another
folded American flag?

1374
01:51:15,454 --> 01:51:17,872
Tell her that when you found me,

1375
01:51:17,956 --> 01:51:21,626
I was here and I was
with the only brothers that I have left,

1376
01:51:21,752 --> 01:51:24,962
and that there's no way
I was gonna desert them.

1377
01:51:26,131 --> 01:51:28,299
I think she'll understand that.

1378
01:51:28,425 --> 01:51:31,385
There's no way I'm leaving this bridge.

1379
01:52:14,388 --> 01:52:16,472
What are your orders?

1380
01:52:18,308 --> 01:52:21,644
Sergeant, we have crossed
some strange boundary here.

1381
01:52:22,646 --> 01:52:25,231
The world has taken a turn
for the surreal.

1382
01:52:25,315 --> 01:52:28,150
Clearly, but the question still stands.

1383
01:52:28,819 --> 01:52:31,821
I don't know. What do you think?

1384
01:52:32,864 --> 01:52:35,658
HORVATH: You don't want to know
what I think.

1385
01:52:37,536 --> 01:52:39,203
No, Mike, I do.

1386
01:52:40,914 --> 01:52:44,208
Well, part of me thinks the kid's right.

1387
01:52:44,334 --> 01:52:46,836
What's he done to deserve this?

1388
01:52:46,920 --> 01:52:50,881
He wants to stay here, fine,
let's leave him and go home.

1389
01:52:52,175 --> 01:52:53,426
Yeah.

1390
01:52:54,011 --> 01:52:59,098
But another part of me thinks
what if, by some miracle, we stay

1391
01:52:59,182 --> 01:53:01,851
and actually make it out of here?

1392
01:53:02,728 --> 01:53:06,355
Someday we might look back on this
and decide that

1393
01:53:06,440 --> 01:53:09,859
saving Private Ryan
was the one decent thing

1394
01:53:09,943 --> 01:53:12,862
we were able to pull out of this whole

1395
01:53:12,946 --> 01:53:15,072
God-awful, shitty mess.

1396
01:53:16,742 --> 01:53:19,243
That's what I was thinking, sir.

1397
01:53:20,412 --> 01:53:22,580
Like you said, Captain,

1398
01:53:24,374 --> 01:53:26,083
we do that,

1399
01:53:26,543 --> 01:53:29,378
we all earn the right to go home.

1400
01:53:32,215 --> 01:53:33,758
Oh, brother.

1401
01:53:37,220 --> 01:53:39,555
TRASK: This is everything.

1402
01:53:40,265 --> 01:53:45,895
You got the two 30-calibre machine
guns, 17 grenades, 11 Hawkins mines.

1403
01:53:46,646 --> 01:53:49,982
You got the two bazookas,
but they only got eight rounds left,

1404
01:53:50,067 --> 01:53:52,276
and assorted small arms.

1405
01:53:52,402 --> 01:53:55,863
We had a 60 mortar
but an arty round took it out.

1406
01:53:55,947 --> 01:53:58,616
Might as well be spit wads
if they roll on us with tanks.

1407
01:53:58,742 --> 01:54:01,952
- Which they're sure to do.
- What are you thinking, sir?

1408
01:54:02,079 --> 01:54:06,665
Well, I'm thinking they're going to try
to whip around the flanks.

1409
01:54:11,254 --> 01:54:13,506
Unless we can draw
them up this main road here

1410
01:54:13,590 --> 01:54:14,715
in between these buildings

1411
01:54:14,800 --> 01:54:18,761
where all the rubble makes
a bit of a bottleneck.

1412
01:54:18,845 --> 01:54:20,888
- Disable 'em?
- If we can.

1413
01:54:20,972 --> 01:54:22,556
Make that tank a 60-ton roadblock.

1414
01:54:22,641 --> 01:54:24,475
We do that, we got
a fighting chance at their flanks.

1415
01:54:24,601 --> 01:54:26,977
Yes, sir that's good. Split them up.
Don't let them mass anywhere.

1416
01:54:27,104 --> 01:54:30,022
Hit them hard as we can, one-on-one,
and fall back to the bridge.

1417
01:54:30,107 --> 01:54:32,316
Machine gun on the move down here,
and number two up high somewhere

1418
01:54:32,442 --> 01:54:34,443
to piss a little bad news down
on their heads.

1419
01:54:34,528 --> 01:54:36,779
MILLER: That would be the idea.

1420
01:54:37,322 --> 01:54:38,781
Jackson.

1421
01:54:39,449 --> 01:54:41,700
If we can, I'd like to get you up
in that bell tower.

1422
01:54:41,785 --> 01:54:44,829
- Yes, sir.
- Give you a little company if you need it.

1423
01:54:44,955 --> 01:54:46,956
Yes, sir. Some company couldn't hurt.

1424
01:54:47,040 --> 01:54:51,085
I'd say a. 30 with about
1,000 rounds would be okay.

1425
01:54:51,169 --> 01:54:53,212
Parker, job opportunity.

1426
01:54:53,296 --> 01:54:55,297
Yeah. Well, it's not the worst idea
ever, Captain.

