01:54:55,382 --> 01:54:56,966
It's just that everything depends
on getting the tank

1428
01:54:57,050 --> 01:54:59,135
down this main road for us
to knock out, right?

1429
01:54:59,302 --> 01:55:02,304
So how the hell do you
plan on doing that?

1430
01:55:02,806 --> 01:55:03,806
HORVATH: Reiben's right.

1431
01:55:03,890 --> 01:55:05,724
As our esteemed colleague
from the Airborne pointed out,

1432
01:55:05,809 --> 01:55:08,102
what we got here are
a bunch of spit wads,

1433
01:55:08,186 --> 01:55:12,022
so how do we stop the tank
if we get it to commit?

1434
01:55:12,149 --> 01:55:14,525
Give it a rabbit to chase.

1435
01:55:14,651 --> 01:55:17,778
We could hit the tank in the tracks.

1436
01:55:17,863 --> 01:55:19,989
Yeah, but with what?

1437
01:55:21,658 --> 01:55:25,494
- Well, we could try a sticky bomb.
- RYAN: Sticky bomb, sir?

1438
01:55:26,705 --> 01:55:30,541
- Sir, are you making that up?
- No. It's in the field manual.

1439
01:55:30,667 --> 01:55:32,501
You check it out if you want to.

1440
01:55:32,586 --> 01:55:34,670
RYAN: We seem to be out
of field manuals, sir.

1441
01:55:34,754 --> 01:55:36,672
Perhaps you can enlighten us?

1442
01:55:36,756 --> 01:55:38,215
All right, you have
some demolition, don't you?

1443
01:55:38,341 --> 01:55:40,259
Some TNT or some composition B?

1444
01:55:40,343 --> 01:55:42,052
Yeah, that, sir, is the one thing
we got plenty of.

1445
01:55:42,179 --> 01:55:44,805
I got that bridge wired with enough
composition B to blow it twice.

1446
01:55:44,890 --> 01:55:46,891
All right. You can spare some, then.

1447
01:55:47,017 --> 01:55:50,227
You take a standard-issue Gl sock,

1448
01:55:50,353 --> 01:55:53,439
cram it with as much
comp B as it can hold,

1449
01:55:53,523 --> 01:55:55,983
rig up a simple fuse,

1450
01:55:56,067 --> 01:55:58,611
then you coat the whole thing
with axle grease.

1451
01:55:58,695 --> 01:56:03,199
That way, when you throw it,
it should stick. It's a bomb that sticks.

1452
01:56:03,283 --> 01:56:04,909
It's a sticky bomb.

1453
01:56:05,035 --> 01:56:07,411
You come up with a better way
to knock the tracks off a tank,

1454
01:56:07,537 --> 01:56:09,121
I'm all ears.

1455
01:56:09,206 --> 01:56:12,750
This is good.
Now we got to surrender our socks.

1456
01:56:27,224 --> 01:56:28,724
Haul away.

1457
01:56:42,739 --> 01:56:46,659
All right, select the field of fire.
Crossfire with the one in the bell tower.

1458
01:56:46,743 --> 01:56:50,079
All right, I can cover
12 to nine from here.

1459
01:56:53,291 --> 01:56:55,417
- Easy!
- I got her!

1460
01:57:29,786 --> 01:57:31,620
Here are the mines.

1461
01:57:42,549 --> 01:57:44,967
For being the best we can do,

1462
01:57:45,051 --> 01:57:49,054
that forward machine gun
is not in a terrible firing position.

1463
01:57:51,725 --> 01:57:54,226
And this position right here,

1464
01:57:56,313 --> 01:57:57,896
this is the Alamo.

1465
01:57:58,481 --> 01:58:02,151
They push us back this far,
last man alive blows the bridge.

1466
01:58:02,235 --> 01:58:04,278
We only got a 30-second delay
on that fuse,

1467
01:58:04,362 --> 01:58:06,405
so let everyone know that
if you are that last man

1468
01:58:06,489 --> 01:58:10,576
you better hurry your ass off,
or you're not going to be alive long.

1469
01:58:10,660 --> 01:58:14,079
Captain? Where am I during all this?

1470
01:58:14,998 --> 01:58:16,957
Never more than
two feet away from me,

1471
01:58:17,042 --> 01:58:19,251
and that's not negotiable.

1472
01:58:20,378 --> 01:58:22,838
I'll get some ammo. Come on.

1473
01:58:25,842 --> 01:58:27,134
- Hey, Upham.
- Yes.

1474
01:58:27,218 --> 01:58:29,094
- Listen to me, all right?
- Yeah.

1475
01:58:29,179 --> 01:58:30,721
- You're listening?
- Yes.

1476
01:58:30,847 --> 01:58:32,890
All right, we're gonna be displacing

1477
01:58:33,016 --> 01:58:34,600
and falling back like crazy
sons of bitches.

1478
01:58:34,684 --> 01:58:35,768
Right up there.

1479
01:58:35,852 --> 01:58:39,313
So you got to be Johnny on the spot
with the ammo, or we're dead.

1480
01:58:39,397 --> 01:58:41,106
- Right.
- You understand that?

1481
01:58:41,191 --> 01:58:43,484
- Johnny on the spot.
- Yeah.

1482
01:58:43,568 --> 01:58:46,695
- You all right?
- Yeah. Yes.

1483
01:58:47,030 --> 01:58:48,280
You know, when we were
shipping out of England

1484
01:58:48,365 --> 01:58:50,324
the supply sergeant was handing
out cartons of cigarettes,

1485
01:58:50,408 --> 01:58:53,535
and I said "No, thank you,
I don't smoke."

1486
01:58:54,537 --> 01:58:56,121
"I don't smoke."

1487
01:58:57,957 --> 01:59:00,918
- Quite a situation, huh?
- Unbelievable.

1488
01:59:02,253 --> 01:59:07,800
Here. Fucked up beyond
all recognition, right?

1489
01:59:08,259 --> 01:59:10,135
You got that right.

1490
01:59:12,389 --> 01:59:13,764
FUBAR.

1491
01:59:16,101 --> 01:59:17,142
Ouch.

1492
01:59:17,435 --> 01:59:19,061
- Yeah, well...
- FUBAR.

1493
01:59:19,145 --> 01:59:21,647
It's going to be a real show, huh?

1494
01:59:21,731 --> 01:59:23,649
Yeah. Okay.

1495
01:59:29,906 --> 01:59:31,573
Take it easy.

1496
01:59:32,742 --> 01:59:34,201
FUBAR.

1497
02:00:10,989 --> 02:00:12,030
(WOMAN ON RADIO SINGING)

1498
02:00:12,115 --> 02:00:16,452
- RYAN: Who's that singing, sir?
- Edith Piaf.

1499
02:00:18,872 --> 02:00:21,415
RYAN: What's she so upset about?

1500
02:00:22,250 --> 02:00:23,792
Her lover left her,

1501
02:00:23,918 --> 02:00:27,379
but she still sees his face
everywhere she goes.

1502
02:00:28,548 --> 02:00:30,466
That would do it.

1503
02:00:59,746 --> 02:01:02,706
"Even life itself only represents you.

1504
02:01:05,835 --> 02:01:08,420
"Sometimes I dream
that I'm in your arms."

1505
02:01:08,505 --> 02:01:10,923
What was that part?
She sang that before.

1506
02:01:11,007 --> 02:01:13,383
- The chorus. It's the chorus.
- The chorus.

1507
02:01:14,135 --> 02:01:16,762
"And you speak softly in my ear

1508
02:01:18,640 --> 02:01:21,058
"and you say things

1509
02:01:21,142 --> 02:01:23,560
"that make my eyes close.

1510
02:01:25,897 --> 02:01:27,981
"And I find that marvellous."

1511
02:01:28,066 --> 02:01:30,692
- Again, Upham...
- Yes.

1512
02:01:31,402 --> 02:01:35,781
...to be honest with you,
I find myself curiously aroused by you.

1513
02:01:35,865 --> 02:01:36,824
(MEN LAUGHING)

1514
02:01:36,908 --> 02:01:40,410
- Marvellous.
- No, it's really a melancholy song.

1515
02:01:40,537 --> 02:01:44,206
At the beginning of the song, she says,
"And then one day, you left.

1516
02:01:44,332 --> 02:01:48,335
"You left me, and I've been
desperate ever since.

1517
02:01:48,419 --> 02:01:51,588
"I see you all over the sky,
I see you all over the Earth."

1518
02:01:51,714 --> 02:01:53,340
Jesus, Upham,
any more songs like this,

1519
02:01:53,424 --> 02:01:55,133
the krauts aren't going
to have to shoot me.

1520
02:01:55,218 --> 02:01:58,053
I'm just going to slit my own wrists.

1521
02:01:58,179 --> 02:02:00,848
You know,
you're a strange bird, Upham.

1522
02:02:00,932 --> 02:02:02,808
Sorry, it's Edith, you know.

1523
02:02:02,892 --> 02:02:04,893
You know what
that song reminds me of?

1524
02:02:05,019 --> 02:02:07,688
It reminds me of Mrs Rachel Troubowitz
and what she said to me

1525
02:02:07,772 --> 02:02:09,273
the day I left for basic.

1526
02:02:09,399 --> 02:02:11,900
What, "Don't touch me"?

1527
02:02:12,026 --> 02:02:14,570
No. Mrs Rachel Troubowitz
is our super's wife.

1528
02:02:14,696 --> 02:02:17,489
She comes into my mom's shop
to try on a few things, all right?

1529
02:02:17,574 --> 02:02:21,368
And she's easily, like, a 44 double E.

1530
02:02:21,452 --> 02:02:23,078
- Double E?
- These things are massive.

1531
02:02:23,204 --> 02:02:24,413
Those are big.

1532
02:02:24,539 --> 02:02:27,875
No. And I've got her convinced
that she's, like, a 42 D, all right?

1533
02:02:27,959 --> 02:02:29,668
So we're in the dressing room,
she's trying to squeeze

1534
02:02:29,752 --> 02:02:33,255
into this side-cut,
silk-ribboned, triple-panel girdle

1535
02:02:33,381 --> 02:02:35,549
with the shelf-lift brassiere.

1536
02:02:35,633 --> 02:02:38,218
And it's beautiful 'cause she's just
pouring out of this thing, you know?

1537
02:02:38,303 --> 02:02:40,053
- Is it really tight?
- No, no. It's beautiful.

1538
02:02:40,138 --> 02:02:41,597
And she sees me, and she can tell

1539
02:02:41,723 --> 02:02:44,308
I got a hard-on the size
of the Statue of Liberty, all right?

1540
02:02:44,434 --> 02:02:46,435
And she says to me,
"Richard, calm down."

1541
02:02:46,561 --> 02:02:49,021
And she says, "When you're over there,

1542
02:02:49,105 --> 02:02:50,981
"if you see anything that upsets you,

1543
02:02:51,107 --> 02:02:54,151
"or if you're ever scared,
I want you to close your eyes

1544
02:02:54,277 --> 02:02:57,279
"and think of these. You understand?"

1545
02:02:58,781 --> 02:03:00,908
So I said, "Yes, ma'am."

1546
02:03:14,088 --> 02:03:16,131
RYAN: Are you all right, sir?

1547
02:03:17,133 --> 02:03:19,927
Yeah, I'm just keeping the rhythm.

1548
02:03:24,807 --> 02:03:27,768
Is it true you were
a teacher back home?

1549
02:03:28,811 --> 02:03:30,270
Yes.

1550
02:03:30,355 --> 02:03:32,689
See, that's something I could never do,
you know.

1551
02:03:32,815 --> 02:03:37,277
Not after the way me and my brothers
treated our teachers. No, sir.

1552
02:03:39,614 --> 02:03:42,032
I had 1,000 kids like you.

1553
02:03:48,289 --> 02:03:50,999
I can't see my brothers' faces.

1554
02:03:52,335 --> 02:03:55,003
I've been trying,
and I can't see their faces at all.

1555
02:03:55,129 --> 02:03:57,297
Has that ever happened to you?

1556
02:03:57,382 --> 02:03:59,800
You gotta think of a context.

1557
02:04:02,011 --> 02:04:04,096
What does that mean?

1558
02:04:04,180 --> 02:04:05,722
Well, you don't just think
about their faces.

1559
02:04:05,848 --> 02:04:10,477
You think about something specific,
something you've done together.

1560
02:04:14,190 --> 02:04:17,150
Well, when I think of home,
I think of something specific.

1561
02:04:17,235 --> 02:04:20,362
I think of my hammock in the backyard,

1562
02:04:21,197 --> 02:04:25,534
or my wife pruning the rose bushes
in a pair of my old work gloves.

1563
02:04:29,831 --> 02:04:33,125
This one night, two of my brothers came

1564
02:04:33,209 --> 02:04:36,211
and woke me up in
the middle of the night,

1565
02:04:37,046 --> 02:04:40,090
and they said
they had a surprise for me.

1566
02:04:40,675 --> 02:04:43,802
So they took me to the barn,
up into the loft,

1567
02:04:43,886 --> 02:04:46,888
and there was my oldest brother Dan

1568
02:04:48,016 --> 02:04:51,059
(LAUGHING) with Alice. Alice Jardine.

1569
02:04:54,063 --> 02:04:58,233
I mean, picture a girl who just took
a nosedive from the ugly tree

1570
02:04:58,359 --> 02:05:00,944
and hit every branch coming down.

1571
02:05:02,905 --> 02:05:05,532
And Dan's got her shirt off.

1572
02:05:05,616 --> 02:05:08,410
So he's working on this bra
and he's trying to get it off

1573
02:05:08,536 --> 02:05:11,747
and all of a sudden,
Sean just screams out,

1574
02:05:12,582 --> 02:05:15,917
"Danny, you're a young man!
Don't do it!"

1575
02:05:18,588 --> 02:05:22,090
And so Alice Jardine hears this
and she screams, and she jumps up,

1576
02:05:22,216 --> 02:05:23,842
and she tries to get
running out of the barn,

1577
02:05:23,926 --> 02:05:25,135
but she's still got this shirt
over her head.

1578
02:05:25,261 --> 02:05:29,431
She goes running right into the wall
and knocks herself out.

1579
02:05:29,557 --> 02:05:33,727
So now Dan is just so mad at us,
he starts coming after us,

1580
02:05:33,811 --> 02:05:36,188
but at the same time,
Alice is over there unconscious.

1581
02:05:36,272 --> 02:05:37,773
He's got to wake her up.

1582
02:05:37,899 --> 02:05:41,151
So he grabs her by a leg
and he's dragging her.

1583
02:05:41,277 --> 02:05:44,446
At the same time, he picks up a shovel
and he's going after Sean.

1584
02:05:44,572 --> 02:05:46,698
And Sean said,
"What are you trying to hit me for?

1585
02:05:46,783 --> 02:05:48,909
"I just did you a favour."

1586
02:05:50,745 --> 02:05:52,621
And so this makes Dan more angry.

1587
02:05:52,747 --> 02:05:55,665
He tries to swing this thing.
He loses the shovel.

1588
02:05:55,792 --> 02:05:58,460
It goes out of his grasp
and hits a kerosene lantern.

1589
02:05:58,586 --> 02:06:01,171
The thing explodes,
the whole barn almost goes up

1590
02:06:01,297 --> 02:06:03,465
because of this thing.

1591
02:06:18,314 --> 02:06:20,190
That was it. That was the last...
That was...

1592
02:06:20,316 --> 02:06:21,858
Dan went off to basic next day.

1593
02:06:21,984 --> 02:06:25,570
That was the last night
the four of us were together.

1594
02:06:25,655 --> 02:06:27,781
That was two years ago.

1595
02:06:29,659 --> 02:06:31,034
Oh, my.

1596
02:06:32,995 --> 02:06:36,540
Tell me about your wife
and those rose bushes.

1597
02:06:37,792 --> 02:06:39,167
No.

1598
02:06:40,336 --> 02:06:43,046
No. That one I save just for me.

1599
02:06:45,842 --> 02:06:48,051
(SINGING ON RADIO CONTINUES)

1600
02:07:03,693 --> 02:07:05,944
(DISTANT RUMBLING)

1601
02:07:22,628 --> 02:07:23,753
(MUSIC STOPS)

1602
02:07:48,362 --> 02:07:50,238
MILLER: Enemy from the east.

1603
02:07:51,407 --> 02:07:54,326
He sees Tiger tanks, two of them.

1604
02:07:54,410 --> 02:07:56,411
Panzer tanks, two of them.

1605
02:07:56,537 --> 02:07:58,330
Infantry.

1606
02:07:58,414 --> 02:08:00,290
Fifty plus change.

1607
02:08:09,258 --> 02:08:11,009
Disperse! You know what to do!

1608
02:08:11,093 --> 02:08:12,636
- Reiben, get on the rabbit.
- Yes, sir.

1609
02:08:12,762 --> 02:08:14,012
Upham, get some cover.

1610
02:08:14,096 --> 02:08:16,097
MILLER: Mellish and Henderson,
lock and load!

1611
02:08:16,224 --> 02:08:19,142
- This is it.
- MILLER: Everybody check your ammo!

1612
02:08:19,810 --> 02:08:21,102
Good luck, Reiben.

1613
02:08:21,229 --> 02:08:24,564
I don't need any luck, Sarge,
I was born lucky.

1614
02:08:37,328 --> 02:08:38,620
One in five tracer?

1615
02:08:38,704 --> 02:08:40,705
Yep, and tracers point both ways.

1616
02:08:40,790 --> 02:08:44,834
Yeah? Why don't you check
the head space and she should run.

1617
02:08:52,677 --> 02:08:54,886
Upham! Hustle up!

1618
02:09:01,394 --> 02:09:03,019
(TANKS RUMBLING)

1619
02:09:45,229 --> 02:09:46,896
- Corporal Upham?
- Yes, sir.

1620
02:09:47,023 --> 02:09:49,274
We don't have a 30-calibre
machine gun in this position.

1621
02:09:49,358 --> 02:09:52,736
Either Mr Mellish or Mr Jackson
in the bell tower needs that.

1622
02:09:52,862 --> 02:09:54,195
Yes, sir.

1623
02:09:55,031 --> 02:09:57,282
Upham! Jackson's fine.
Turn around to Mellish.

1624
02:09:57,366 --> 02:09:59,034
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

1625
02:10:19,680 --> 02:10:22,432
There's a ton of infantry, Captain.
I don't know if they took the bait though.

1626
02:10:22,516 --> 02:10:24,267
(TANKS APPROACHING)

1627
02:10:47,458 --> 02:10:49,584
You got any more of that?

1628
02:11:21,367 --> 02:11:23,159
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1629
02:11:35,756 --> 02:11:38,091
Panzers didn't take the bait.

1630
02:11:43,013 --> 02:11:45,849
Infantry's moving to the left.

1631
02:11:45,933 --> 02:11:49,310
Halftrack just went by
with about 20 troops, sir.

1632
02:12:17,923 --> 02:12:20,049
(SHOUTING ORDERS IN GERMAN)

1633
02:13:27,993 --> 02:13:31,329
Mellish! Henderson! Displace!

1634
02:13:34,124 --> 02:13:35,917
(CONTINUOUS GUNFIRE)

1635
02:13:52,893 --> 02:13:54,686
Do it, now! Light it up!

1636
02:13:54,770 --> 02:13:56,563
You! Light it!

1637
02:14:07,741 --> 02:14:09,867
Thirty infantry on the right flank!

1638
02:14:09,952 --> 02:14:12,453
Get over there,
find a hole, and stop them!

1639
02:14:12,538 --> 02:14:14,038
Displace!

1640
02:14:14,123 --> 02:14:15,623
(TANK ROLLING)

1641
02:14:25,801 --> 02:14:27,093
Upham!

1642
02:14:42,484 --> 02:14:43,943
Clear!

1643
02:14:45,738 --> 02:14:46,988
Krauts!

1644
02:14:48,991 --> 02:14:50,491
Right flank!

1645
02:15:02,796 --> 02:15:04,589
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1646
02:15:26,945 --> 02:15:29,113
Get down! Get down!

1647
02:15:36,163 --> 02:15:39,290
Upham! Upham! 30-cal! Hurry!

1648
02:15:39,375 --> 02:15:42,877
And find the captain!
This flank's going to fold!

1649
02:16:00,771 --> 02:16:02,605
(BULLETS WHIZZING BY)

1650
02:16:19,915 --> 02:16:21,249
(SHOUTING)

1651
02:16:37,766 --> 02:16:40,560
Reversing! He's still in this fight!

1652
02:16:41,562 --> 02:16:44,105
No, no, Ryan, get down! Get down!

1653
02:16:57,035 --> 02:16:58,286
Ryan!

1654
02:17:17,473 --> 02:17:18,890
Ryan!

1655
02:17:21,226 --> 02:17:22,810
- Ryan!
- RYAN: Get off me!

1656
02:17:22,936 --> 02:17:25,396
- Are you all right?
- Get off me!

1657
02:17:25,481 --> 02:17:27,648
Yeah, yeah,
I'm fine, too, Captain. Thanks.

1658
02:17:28,484 --> 02:17:33,029
MILLER: Okay, both sides!
Get aboard! Get a grenade in there!

1659
02:17:33,113 --> 02:17:34,322
(COUGHS)

1660
02:17:36,116 --> 02:17:37,617
Grenade!

1661
02:17:39,453 --> 02:17:41,120
20-mill!

1662
02:17:42,581 --> 02:17:45,291
Flak gun, 20 millimetre. Take it out!

1663
02:17:57,638 --> 02:18:01,182
Heavy weapon in defilade below!
I ain't got a shot!

1664
02:18:05,687 --> 02:18:07,396
Pincer move, Parker!

1665
02:18:07,523 --> 02:18:09,982
- Targets 8 o'clock low!
- Shit!

1666
02:18:10,067 --> 02:18:12,318
God grant me strength.

1667
02:18:19,952 --> 02:18:21,744
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1668
02:18:26,208 --> 02:18:27,750
Displace!

1669
02:18:27,876 --> 02:18:29,252
Come on!

1670
02:18:33,048 --> 02:18:34,423
(SCREAMING)

1671
02:18:45,060 --> 02:18:47,812
MILLER: Cover, Upham! Cover! Cover!

1672
02:19:04,580 --> 02:19:06,581
MELLISH: I'm out of 30-calibre.

1673
02:19:09,960 --> 02:19:12,837
Blessed be the Lord, my strength,
which teaches my hands to war

1674
02:19:12,921 --> 02:19:15,256
and my fingers to fight.

1675
02:19:23,765 --> 02:19:26,267
My goodness and my fortress,

1676
02:19:26,351 --> 02:19:29,020
my high tower and my deliverer,

1677
02:19:31,607 --> 02:19:34,817
my shield and he in whom I trust.

1678
02:19:37,863 --> 02:19:39,947
Come here, baby.

1679
02:20:02,554 --> 02:20:04,347
Parker, get down!

1680
02:20:26,036 --> 02:20:28,454
Captain, that 20-millimetre's killing us.

1681
02:20:28,538 --> 02:20:30,831
We gotta try to flank it somehow.

1682
02:20:30,958 --> 02:20:33,834
Well, let me get over for the top shot.

1683
02:20:49,518 --> 02:20:51,560
(TANK RAPIDLY APPROACHING)

1684
02:20:58,318 --> 02:20:59,735
HENDERSON: Upham!

1685
02:21:08,453 --> 02:21:09,870
(EXPLOSIONS)

1686
02:21:18,588 --> 02:21:23,050
Upham! Upham!
Upham, ammo, God damn it!

1687
02:21:48,368 --> 02:21:50,161
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN)

1688
02:22:06,261 --> 02:22:08,679
I'm jammed! I'm jammed!
You got any 30-cal?

1689
02:22:08,764 --> 02:22:10,431
- I'm out.
- Shit.

1690
02:22:11,308 --> 02:22:13,267
(BANGING)

1691
02:22:22,277 --> 02:22:24,779
Upham! Upham!

1692
02:22:31,578 --> 02:22:32,745
(THUD)

1693
02:23:04,736 --> 02:23:06,028
(GASPING)

1694
02:23:22,921 --> 02:23:24,380
Reiben!

1695
02:23:30,220 --> 02:23:31,637
(SHOUTING)

1696
02:23:50,866 --> 02:23:55,035
I'm out! I need another bandoleer!
Anybody got a bandoleer?

1697
02:24:17,893 --> 02:24:19,393
(YELLING)

1698
02:24:20,061 --> 02:24:22,229
God! God!

1699
02:24:26,526 --> 02:24:29,445
You stupid son of a bitch!

1700
02:24:35,118 --> 02:24:36,744
(YELLING)

1701
02:25:09,402 --> 02:25:11,153
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1702
02:25:13,114 --> 02:25:15,658
Let's stop. Let's stop. Let's stop.
Listen to me! Listen to me! Stop!

1703
02:25:15,742 --> 02:25:17,493
Stop! Don't...

1704
02:25:21,289 --> 02:25:23,082
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1705
02:25:25,502 --> 02:25:26,794
(CHOKING)

1706
02:25:28,755 --> 02:25:30,130
(SHUSHING)

1707
02:25:44,771 --> 02:25:46,480
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1708
02:25:54,531 --> 02:25:59,368
Son of a bitch!
Son of a bitch! Son of a bitch!

1709
02:25:59,452 --> 02:26:01,245
Son of a bitch!

1710
02:26:02,706 --> 02:26:03,747
Bitch!

1711
02:26:52,339 --> 02:26:53,714
(SOBBING)

1712
02:27:03,558 --> 02:27:05,392
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1713
02:27:22,786 --> 02:27:25,913
- I'm out.
- Those 60 rounds.

1714
02:27:27,290 --> 02:27:30,459
- We can use them without the tube.
- How?

1715
02:27:30,543 --> 02:27:33,504
Fuse-arming wire, set back, heave it!

1716
02:27:49,229 --> 02:27:50,896
Panzerschreck!

1717
02:28:24,973 --> 02:28:27,182
We're going to the Alamo.

1718
02:28:37,444 --> 02:28:39,278
Alamo! Alamo!

1719
02:28:42,866 --> 02:28:44,658
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1720
02:28:58,840 --> 02:29:01,133
We'll take it! You fall back!

1721
02:29:01,217 --> 02:29:04,845
- You be right behind us!
- Soon as we're in business!

1722
02:29:08,808 --> 02:29:10,893
Displace. Reiben.

1723
02:29:13,396 --> 02:29:14,855
Reload.

1724
02:29:16,357 --> 02:29:18,150
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1725
02:30:03,655 --> 02:30:05,197
All right, go.

1726
02:30:06,449 --> 02:30:07,533
We're blowing the bridge!

1727
02:30:07,617 --> 02:30:10,536
- Get off! Clear the bridge!
- Displace...

1728
02:30:13,248 --> 02:30:14,706
(HORVATH EXCLAIMS)

1729
02:30:33,393 --> 02:30:36,395
MILLER: Sarge! Mike, are you all right?

1730
02:30:36,479 --> 02:30:39,022
- I just got the wind knocked out of me.
- Well, get out of here!

1731
02:30:39,107 --> 02:30:42,484
Take cover!
We're going to blow this bridge!

1732
02:30:43,945 --> 02:30:45,696
Come on, come on!

1733
02:30:50,493 --> 02:30:53,328
Tiger coming!
Coming across the bridge!

1734
02:30:54,497 --> 02:30:56,290
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1735
02:31:25,403 --> 02:31:28,697
(FAINTLY) Captain,
get behind something!

1736
02:31:28,781 --> 02:31:31,450
(FAINTLY) Come on, Captain, move it!

1737
02:31:54,390 --> 02:31:55,599
Mike.

1738
02:32:00,813 --> 02:32:02,147
Mike!

1739
02:32:18,790 --> 02:32:20,540
(BULLET BUZZING)

1740
02:32:41,145 --> 02:32:42,437
REIBEN: Captain.

1741
02:32:45,233 --> 02:32:49,319
Captain, where the hell are you going?
Captain, get back here!

1742
02:34:28,836 --> 02:34:30,670
(ORDERING IN GERMAN)

1743
02:34:42,391 --> 02:34:43,725
Upham.

1744
02:35:14,715 --> 02:35:16,925
Hang in there, Captain.

1745
02:36:01,053 --> 02:36:02,762
REIBEN: Medic!

1746
02:36:05,558 --> 02:36:08,101
Medic! We got a medic?

1747
02:36:14,901 --> 02:36:17,777
They're tank-busters, sir. P-51 s.

1748
02:36:18,738 --> 02:36:20,947
Angels on our shoulders.

1749
02:36:26,913 --> 02:36:28,622
What, sir?

1750
02:36:33,085 --> 02:36:34,461
James...

1751
02:36:36,255 --> 02:36:37,756
Earn this.

1752
02:36:42,011 --> 02:36:43,470
Earn it.

1753
02:37:12,917 --> 02:37:15,085
MARSHALL: "My dear Mrs Ryan,

1754
02:37:16,337 --> 02:37:18,797
"it's with the most profound sense ofjoy

1755
02:37:18,881 --> 02:37:24,052
"that I write to inform you
your son Private James Ryan

1756
02:37:24,178 --> 02:37:26,262
"is well and, at this very moment,

1757
02:37:26,347 --> 02:37:29,808
"on his way home
from European battlefields.

1758
02:37:29,892 --> 02:37:33,395
"Reports from the front indicate
James did his duty in combat

1759
02:37:33,521 --> 02:37:37,023
"with great courage
and steadfast dedication,

1760
02:37:37,608 --> 02:37:40,193
"even after he was informed
of the tragic loss

1761
02:37:40,277 --> 02:37:43,863
"your family has suffered
in this great campaign

1762
02:37:43,948 --> 02:37:47,367
"to rid the world
of tyranny and oppression.

1763
02:37:47,451 --> 02:37:50,704
"I take great pleasure in joining
the Secretary of War,

1764
02:37:50,871 --> 02:37:52,956
"the men and women
of the United States Army

1765
02:37:53,040 --> 02:37:55,417
"and the citizens of a grateful nation

1766
02:37:55,543 --> 02:37:58,420
"in wishing you good health
and many years of happiness

1767
02:37:58,546 --> 02:38:01,047
"with James at your side.

1768
02:38:02,216 --> 02:38:06,219
"Nothing, not even the safe
return of a beloved son,

1769
02:38:06,303 --> 02:38:07,846
"can compensate you

1770
02:38:07,930 --> 02:38:10,974
"or the thousands
of other American families

1771
02:38:11,058 --> 02:38:14,436
"who have suffered great loss
in this tragic war.

1772
02:38:14,562 --> 02:38:18,023
"And I might share with you some words
which have sustained me

1773
02:38:18,107 --> 02:38:22,235
"through long, dark nights of peril,
loss and heartache.

1774
02:38:22,319 --> 02:38:23,778
"And I quote,

1775
02:38:25,114 --> 02:38:26,698
"'I pray that our heavenly father

1776
02:38:26,782 --> 02:38:29,993
"'may assuage the anguish
of your bereavement

1777
02:38:30,077 --> 02:38:32,037
"'and leave you only
the cherished memory

1778
02:38:32,121 --> 02:38:34,122
"'of the loved and lost

1779
02:38:34,248 --> 02:38:36,583
"'and the solemn pride
that must be yours

1780
02:38:36,667 --> 02:38:41,421
"'to have laid so costly a sacrifice
upon the altar of freedom.

1781
02:38:42,173 --> 02:38:43,840
"'Abraham Lincoln. '

1782
02:38:44,425 --> 02:38:46,843
"Yours very sincerely and respectfully,

1783
02:38:46,927 --> 02:38:50,263
"George C Marshall,
General, Chief of Staff."

1784
02:39:41,649 --> 02:39:43,983
My family is with me today.

1785
02:39:44,944 --> 02:39:47,779
They wanted to come with me.

1786
02:39:49,448 --> 02:39:50,573
To be honest with you,

1787
02:39:50,658 --> 02:39:53,952
I wasn't sure how I'd feel
coming back here.

1788
02:39:57,331 --> 02:40:00,750
Every day I think about
what you said to me

1789
02:40:00,835 --> 02:40:02,961
that day on the bridge.

1790
02:40:04,839 --> 02:40:08,299
And I've tried to live my life
the best I could.

1791
02:40:09,385 --> 02:40:11,803
I hope that was enough.

1792
02:40:12,555 --> 02:40:15,306
I hope that, at least in your eyes,

1793
02:40:17,143 --> 02:40:20,854
I've earned what all of you
have done for me.

1794
02:40:34,368 --> 02:40:35,702
James.

1795
02:40:37,997 --> 02:40:39,998
"Captain John H Miller."

1796
02:40:48,674 --> 02:40:52,552
- Tell me I've led a good life.
- What?

1797
02:40:53,846 --> 02:40:56,014
Tell me I'm a good man.

1798
02:41:03,230 --> 02:41:04,856
You are.

